author: @lunkel8108

text:
@tastyfood2020 I can just repeat what he said in the video at 2:58.
"The dots don’t each represent a separate electron - the whole collection represents the wavefunction of a single electron, and the individual dots represent all the places that electron could be (a higher density of dots means a higher probability of the electron being there)."
Meaning if you would measure the position of the electron (for such a specific orbital) at a random time, the wave function collapses an you would find the electron at a certain position in space. Now if you repeat this a 1000 times and for every position you measured you would draw a dot in 3 dimensions you would get the visualisation shown in the video. 
At least thats how I understood it.

text:
It is futile to try to understand what an atom looks like.  When we look at a macroscopic object, we see the cumulative effect of countless photons interacting with the material of the object.  An individual electron interacts with an individual photon.  A photon cannot contain information sufficient to make an image.  It contains only momentum, but cannot precisely give the location of the electron, which is in constant motion.  A large number of photons directed at an atom cannot produce an image in the sense that we make images of large objects.  It is meaningless to even think about what an image of an atom would look like.  We can determine that it has a certain mass and occupies some amount of space, that's all.

What we see here, is what a model looks like.  Not the same thing.

In quantum mechanics things really don't work the same as they do on the macro scale.
Things don't work deterministically, rather there is inherent randomness built into every aspect of the particles. They exist EVERYWHERE within that bubble at the same time, until you measure it, where it chooses one point to exist in.

author: @Ivel1oss

text: The problem with such "discussions" is that both parties are usually using the wrong language. An "electron" is a quantum of energy, momentum, angular momentum and charge. If we were to actually measure "an electron" in an atom, then we would destroy the atom. It would not exist after the measurement any longer. This can be done, e.g. with scattering experiments with a high energy beam (of photons, electrons or even other atoms). The result of such a measurement is a scattering angle distribution from which we can reconstruct the wave function (at least partially). We can't do this on a single atom, though. We would need many independent atoms, each of which would be destroyed by the beam interaction. So, at most, we can measure the ensemble average over many atoms. That's NOT ONE electron in motion. That's MANY electrons modifying the beam used to measure them.
author: @lepidoptera9337

text: @lepidoptera9337  I appreciate where you are coming from. Where I am coming from is that I have never studied this. My education is in the arts, and while I can appreciate and understand basic physics and science, but when it gets so advanced it just boggles my mind. My education of the atom is high school science and then anything I’ve learned from watching educational videos since then. And while I can’t speak for the majority of the world, I can say pretty confidently MOST of the world does not have the education to truly understand what people who study quantum physics grasp. So, I think “discussions” are really important between people who understand it and those who don’t. Most of the world needs things presented in a way that they can draw upon current knowledge and make inferences or models of something that actually makes sense. Big things get scaled down. Small things get scaled up. Fast things get scaled down to slower so we can understand the mechanics. This video is great because it gives a picture of something complicated but presented in a way that a layman can digest. And THAT was s my real point here. Education. With the rise of misinformation these days, like climate change being a hoax, or the earth being flat, to the age of the earth being in question it’s important to have difficult topics made digestible to larger audiences. So, no I don’t see a problem with having discussions that are not technically accurate to an expert, but at least it gets more and more people leaning in the right direction.

text:
Honestly don't get what extra information you are getting from these cloud picture (but the clouds are made up from dots). It's literally the same as the orbital pictures. The original just has colours to indicate relative amplitude of the wave function.

IMO this is heading in the wrong direction. Orbitals are NOT similar to planets going around a star, at all. That's the whole point with the electron cloud model, to get away from the false depiction of electrons orbiting. Moving back towards something that is yet again depicting orbiting around the nucleus in some way, is defeating the purpose.

Electrons live ambiguously in the space that the cloud shows. More likely to be in certain areas, compared to others, but you don't know unless you look. The vagueness of the pictures is on purpose...because that's literally how it is. There is nothing to "improve"

text: I can answer 1. It isn't a force but the fact that the energy required to change orbitals is quantum. It takes a specific and exact amount of energy to raise the orbital to the next valence shell. And when the electron gives back that energy as it can  a photon of the exact same amount of energy is emitted. This was demonstrated to me in high school physics class by burning various chemicals over a Bunsen burner. Different chemicals emit different colors of light because the heat of the flame excites some electrons to rise to a higher valence layer. Then, as they randomly return to their least energetic condition they emit a photon to maintain balance --- which for different chemicals is a different color (frequency aka energy).
author: @garymartin9777

text:
Good questions! Electromagnetic force keeps the electrons around the nucleus. The nucleus and electrons interact by means of virtual photons. That's how this force works. It's an electromagnetic field or exchange of virtual photons. It keeps the electron cloud in some specific shape according to logic or math equations. The electron will be in a specific position when its wave-function collapses. It might be at any random position but it's more likely for it to emerge in points where the density of the electron cloud is higher. It's not just one electron but many of them depending on a specific atom or molecule. 
Perhaps, the double slit experiment might help you understand it better. Once the wave (electrons) passes through two slits and hits the wall, the wave collapses into electrons and we can observe points of their collisions with the wall. We can see an interference pattern as a wave or waves were passing through the two slits. However, if we collapse the waves before they go through the slits (say, by observation), no interference pattern will form on the wall. Each electron then goes only from one slit or another. The same happens if we observe the wave that just passed through the slits but has not hit the wall yet. The wave function collapses again and we have electrons as particles. This time they won't form the interference patter either. Thinking about particles as waves that collapse is a simple model which may have downsides but it's a nice model that can help understand this stuff.
author: @billmorrigan386

text: Very important here is once the wave function collapses after passing through the two slits before hitting the wall, the situation changes and the wave was no longer the wave in the first place! It changes the reality. It means once the electrons got rendered into particles, it's like they were always particles and never were a wave. That's called retrocausality. We don't have a theory that explains it all in a coherent and final way, i.e. what is behind all this, behind the elementary particles, etc. However we do have a number of hypothetical theories that scientists work on and which can explain more, such as string theories. The quantum entanglement experiment proves this conundrum that we had with the double slit experiment leading us to retrocausality and stuff. I mean to various hypothetical theories but no final theory yet. No final explanations. We are going too deep here, I guess.
author: @billmorrigan386

text: OK, let's narrow down the imagery here. . . if we have a single atom of hydrogen, one proton and one electron, in a specific location in which the gravitational influence is nonexistent, and other hydrogen atoms are miles away so that the hydrogen atoms would not bump into each other and there by not influence each other's electron obits, being that the negative charge of the electron would affect the position, at any instant of time, in it's cloud around the proton. Therefore, would this lonely electron be moving around the lonely proton in a specific pattern that is perhaps influenced by the quarks that make up the proton?

text: @billmorrigan386  In reference to wave function vs. particle function concepts. . . I am visualizing waves as a mass of particles changing their position in space measured over time. Waves cannot exist without the presence of particles. Perhaps it is the limitation of our instruments that leaves us with the impression that waves exist without particles. author: @nevenante

text: @nevenante   I get it now. No, a wave here is not a mass of particles. It's not like sea waves or sound waves. These waves are totally different. We don't have answers as to how they propagate in vacuum or what they consist of. At the same time we know that forces are exchanges of virtual particles. In this case, it is specifically virtual photons that the nucleus exchanges with the electron cloud. I think your questions are spot on. I mean we don't really know the nature of these waves, how they propagate in total vacuum and what they consist of. We don't know what causes the wave to collapse (I mean at the deep level) and the particle to emerge as a result, and what causes this retrocausality effect in the double slit experiment or quantum entanglement experiment. We don't know why there are limitations such as the fastest speed possible, the smallest distance possible, the smallest amount of time possible. Why this Planck constant? Why our space is 3-dimensional only (or 4-dimensional with time). These are very deep questions, to which we don't have answers. Some even offer an explanation of our world being some type of digital, pixelated world, almost like some kind of simulation. This explains retrocausality and why particles are not particles until a wave-function collapses. But we don't know that. At this level of depth, it's just speculations.
author: @billmorrigan386

text: Bottom line: we have no idea how electrons move (or if they are even present there in the electron cloud). All we know is that the wave-function collapses and electrons appear. Prior to that it is just an electron cloud which we have no idea about, in terms of what it actually consists of at a deeper level. String theories are flawed and just we just can't find the solution or explanation to make a coherent picture.

text:
Here's one:

A quark is the smallest known thing in the universe, and we arrange three of them in a triangle shape. We convey them as "up" quarks and "down" quarks, but that's just what we call them. Let's say a proton has an up quark, and a neutron has a down quark. Electrons aren't comprised of anything we've observed, so no quarks there.

For the purposes of this, I will pick a water molecule. This has two hydrogen atoms, and one oxygen atom. Hydrogen is simply ¹H, meaning it has 1 nucleon (protons and neutrons) in total. The number of protons always defines the number of electrons for a balance of charges (electrons are negative charged and protons are positive charged). An oxygen atom on the other hand is ¹⁶O, so it has 8 protons and 8 neutrons clumped together.

Electrons are a 2,000th of the size of a proton or neutron (nucleon), and they rotate pretty far away relative to the subatomic scale. Think, from the earth to the sun levels.

If a hydrogen molecule has 1 extra electron, and an oxygen atom has one less electron, the hydrogen atom will donate its electron to the oxygen atom, and thus, the electrons' rotations are now intersected, and this becomes a molecule. We could think of this as:

An oxygen atom has two electrons missing
Two hydrogen atoms, each with an extra electron, come in and bond with the oxygen atom to donate its electron.

If you understood all of that, and you know how to make a 3d animation, send me the link to the video when you're done 👍

In summary:
3 quarks for each nucleon
Up quarks for protons, down quarks for neutrons
Electrons are just electrons
4 protons and 4 neutrons clump together
2 electrons (being 2,000x smaller than nucleons) rotate around this nucleus from a great distance at the subatomic scale.
Two hydrogen atoms (with 2 electrons each) interact their electrons' "orbits" around the nuclei, and therefore they bond.
This creates an accurate diagram of a molecule.

text:
About the rainbow donuts. Wave functions are 3-dimensional waves oscillating into the 4th dimension, which is the complex plane. We call this an imaginary component (even thought it is real). The color indicates that multiplying by the square root of -1 rotates the function around the complex plane by π/2: 
One cycle of the wave function = (+1(aqua) → i(blue/pink) →  -1(red)  →  -i(yellow/green)  →  +1(aqua))

text: Cymatics provides a good visual representation… fine sand particles on a flat surface on top of a speaker, at certain frequencies, create certain patterns.  Similarly, the vibration of the protons will create some unique pattern, around which a 3D “orbital” pattern is observed.  This model is similar to a 3D version of Cymatics.  The presence of an electron as a quantum particle implies a lot… if the particle can be in multiple places at once, then it can permeate the entire universe, but the highest probability is that it will be  located in the valence shell of the atom.  This quantum way of thinking is not ideal in that seeks to quantify everything as a particle.  Some things are not particles, they are fields, which are much more difficult to define in terms of human thinking.  If you doubt my perspective just look at the typical charts of the electromagnetic spectrum and ask yourself how silly it is that we name particles different names at different sections based on the wavelength.  If a photon is a light particle then is there an infrared particle?  What about ultraviolet?  Are there microwave particles called microtrons?  No.  This is just a misapplied understanding of the line between physical matter and vibrational energy.
author: @CharlieMacklin1

text: This is an upgrade, but, what if electrons don’t exist as particles?  I personally don’t think electrons typically exist as particles…not that they can’t exist as a particle, but they don’t.  An electron is better thought of as an “increment of vibration”.  After all, what is a “charge” besides motion..either vibrational or rotational.  I think it’s a better model of existence to place electrons and photons in the category of field waves rather than particles.  Consider the discovery of radio… as voltage and frequency increase, the “electron” density increases towards the outer layer of the wire…if voltage and frequency is high enough, the electron leaves the wire entirely and this is what we call radio.  Now are these particles flying about, or a vibration through some medium that can conduct it? And since radio waves can conduct through the vacuum of space, there must be something there capable of wave transmission.  Light is a similar thing…the waves of light are a vibration propagating through space…”photons” do not exist as particles.  You may be able to quantize them as some increment of measurement, but they are not typically particles.

text:
Please don't invoke deBroglie then draw dots.  There are no dots.  Bear with?  Compare Maxwell's wave solutions inside a spherical resonator with a 20dB sampler (probe).  The sampling-probe measures 1/100th of the power in the resonator (ignore the fact samplers are calibrated to 'modes,' for the moment).  Now insert a single photon into the resonator and ask, what is the probability density function of the photon and where does that function 'collapse' to indicate the photon's position?  The question is preposterous, because the photon is a wave.  A wave that occupies space.  A wave that is not ever located at a point.  (more...) 

Yet the sampler-probe is at a point?  And the sampler only captures the single photon once in a hundred passes (on average)?  So is the probability 'collapsing' or is there simply a probability of capturing the rather large (wrt the sampling-probe) wave as it passes over that sampling probe?  

The answer is obvious.  The photon is a wave.  It's always a wave and never a particle.  Same with the electron bound inside the atom.  Electron is a wave.  It's always a wave.  So draw it as a wave and stop misleading young scientists (including yourself).

text:
Very well presented!  Below is my explanation based on some reading:

Around 450 B.C., the Greek philosopher Democritus introduced the idea of the atom. However, the idea was essentially forgotten for more than 2000 years. In 1800, John Dalton re-introduced the atom. He provided evidence for atoms and developed atomic theory. The concept of of discovering the existence of the atom was very innovative and genius. 

What atoms would look like was predicted using complex calculated mathematical models based on prediction. Roentgen's x-rays allowed scientists to measure the size of the atom. The x-rays were small enough to discern the atomic clouds. This was done by scattering x-rays from atoms and measuring their size just as Rutherford had done earlier by hitting atoms with other nuclei starting with alpha particles. 

Dalton's Model is often referred to as the billiard ball model. He defined an atom to be a ball-like structure, as the concepts of atomic nucleus and electrons were unknown at the time. If you asked Dalton to draw the diagram of an atom, he would've simply drawn a circle! 

A close representation of what an atom looks like:  The photo, taken by David Nadlinger and titled Single Atom In An Ion Trap, is the winner of the Engineering and Physical Sciences Research Council science photography competition. The photo depicts a single strontium atom, embedded inside a strong electric field, blasted by lasers which cause it to emit light.

text:
That's a lot of science-esque words, but it doesn't make much sense...or any sense for that matter...

"Dark matter" is a placeholder for a theoretical substance that gives the universe way more mass than it should have based on our observartions. In other words if it was present in the atom (or anywhere in out reach really) we would detect it as a gravitational anomaly (which is all it really is currently), no such anomaly occurs in atoms or again, anywhere within the reach of modern science. All matter in an atom is accounted for by our current model and "massless dark matter" is an oxymoron

"electron neutrino" and "dark matter muon neutrino" are again just techno-babble, it's the quantum equivalent of saying "water rock". Electron, neutrino and muon are separate particles, there is no such thing as a hybrid between them

"I think photons are a pair of electrons..." - the entire point of photon is that it's a quantum, as far as we know further undividable amount of something, in this case of change of electromagnetic field. That doesn't mean that it actually is undividable of course, we learned our lesson with atom, but if it is it definetly isn't made of anything we know, especially electrons which are lepton particles with actual mass and other properties completely contrary to those of photons


And somehow that's not all

text:
"and some of them because they're questions my brain wants answers to. Like
1. Where is the electron?
2. How fast is it going?"

That's your error -- your brain may want answers to those questions, but the main lesson of quantum mechanics is you don't get answers to all the questions that you want. You have to pick a some questions that will actually get answered and will have to be content with the rest. DeBroglie-Bohm doesn't change this (it can't), as you'll soon realize when you try to extend this model to 2-electron systems and find out you need 6 dimensions to make the visualization work. IOW, the visualization in this video is not an improvement over the usual spherical harmonics visualizations. There's also a bug in it, since particles in eigenstates in Bohmian mechanics remain stationary, so there shouldn't be any movement at all.

text:
If you're confused even after watching this video, read it out....
For your kind information, planets   
don't revolve around the sun in a 3 dimensional way....they do circular motion (not exactly) and as we know that circular motion does not come under 3D motion....
However, an electron in any atom revolves around the nucleus in a 3D way i.e. there are three coordinates that determine the position of an electron at a particular instant....
As we talking of quantum mechanics and not classical mechanics so even the distance between the boundary of nucleus and and what we depict first orbit (n=1) , second orbit(n=2)  and so on... is hundred thousand of times greater than the radius of an electron....
Now let's make it even more simpler to understand;
Just imagine that there is a street   in which so many houses are built one by one , assume that street as an orbit and houses as sub  -shells or sub energy levels and finally each compartment or room of a house as an orbital....
and for moving electrons you can   assume maximum of two mosquitoes that are continuously flying inside the room in a 3D way.....as you can't tell the exact position and exact velocity(speed) or momentum of those mosquitoes simultaneously because their motion is not in our control by the way it is impossible to determine the exact position and exact momentum of a moving electron at the same time according to Heisenberg Uncertainty Principle.....
As some houses have rooms of same dimension and some have rooms of different dimensions by the way some subshells have same kind of orbitals and some of the subshells have orbitals of different orientation.....

Orbital(s) make up a subshell and subshell(s) make up an orbit or a shell....
The 3D region or defined volume in which the probability of finding an electron is maximum, is called orbital and the region in which probability density or the  probability of finding an electron is zero, is termed as node.....
It's my way of explanation so don't worry....
Hope! you got what I wanted to describe 😶

text:
@uttam2274  I didn't say there was no difference between orbits and orbitals ^^'. I even said orbitals were like 3D-shaped orbits, in the sense that an orbit is a bunch of possible positions for a given object just like an orbital is a bunch of possible positions for a given electron.

What I'm not sure of is whether we can say the electron is at all those positions at the same time or if it's got only one position among all those.

If we had a "cannon" to throw photons one at a time, each photon has a single position but all these positions show a wave-like pattern. The double-slit experiment shows it : a single photon gives a dot on the photosensitive screen, but after throwing thousands of photons, you get a wave-like pattern.

My question is : is it the same for electrons? Because electrons aren't thrown by a cannon, they are naturally here, and in limited number, in an atom. For example, a hydrogene atom has a single electron.

If that's the same as the double slit experiment, these clouds only show possible positions but the single electron of an atom would be in a single position in this cloud. In which case, an atom does look like a bunch of balls with several balls around it.

But maybe there's a mysterious effect that makes the shape of the electron literally blurry, making it into a cloud like this? In which case, what is this "mysterious effect"?
author: @Dante02d12

text:
@Dante02d12  Why are you not dealing with quantum mechanics??
Wave particle duality is applicable for a body of length of order 10^-6 m or lower than this order of length.....
An electron moves like a wave around the nucleus and that's why we often get a blurry picture of it.....
Since a photon has a wavelength of order of 10^-14 m which is very small it's wave nature is not observed but in the case of large no. of photons the phenomenon of interference occurs and thus , the resultant wavelength becomes larger and their wave nature is observed....
It's all about wave particle duality of matter and electromagnetic radiation....😶

text:
You could probably use a heat map to assign relative density a shade. I notice apparent motion based upon something. I’d guess likelihood of position and spin? (You specified it’s Angular Momentum.) Anyway you could apply a so called “temperature” to each rendered particle, which increases and decrease by relative proximity? I think. 

My understanding is based in modding Falling Sand games 15 years ago. In Flash if I recall. In those each particle could distribute its “temperature” to particles that touch. Cold to Hot obviously, until they equalize.. 

Here you probably don’t want to render collision, so you’d find a way to measure a trend based on location in a grid. Then map that data in separate layer over your model. Then based on that, have the position of your particle, determine a change in shade for each. Considering you are already rendering particle position, and adding movement, it’s likely possible you could do that. If perhaps technically unfeasible depending what your modeling program is doing, and your expertise.

That’s just theory from a hobbiest game modder. Do with it what you will.

text: "Higher density of dots means a higher probability the electron being there". Even though this is a very popular interpretation of the wave-particle duality, the phrases like that should not be understood literally. This is not because there is no "probability", this is because there is no "being". A more certain and usual formulation is "the probability of finding the particle at a given point". The problem with this formulation is: there is no "finding". We can only talk about the probability of some measurable result of some experiment. "Finding" is a metaphor suggesting that the exact location of a particle does exist, but is inherently stochastic, so we know only the density of the probability of "finding" it for each given point. But what's the experiment to observe the "finding"? The correct interpretation is different: the exact location itself does not exist. We can only indirectly confirm the shapes of the wave function because the theory correctly predicts the experimental results, and this is all that matters. But, fundamentally, we cannot "inspect" the location of a quantum object without the modification of its state.

text: Ummm . . . if you want a picture of where the electron is and how fast it's going, you clearly don't understand how atoms and quantum mechanics work for numerous reasons. First, particles are not extremely tiny spheres. They are excitations in energy fields that permeate the entire universe. Second, the Heisenberg Uncertainty Principle tells us that the more you know about a particle's momentum, which is directly related to its velocity,  the less you know about its position and vice versa. Third, because of quantum tunneling, quantum teleportation, and nonlocality, electrons dont always exist in the orbitals of atoms. An electron can briefly exist in the nucleus. It can travel to the other side of the universe. It can pop in and out of the atom whenever it likes. Finally, particles are not carried along energy fields the way that little specs of dust are carried along water.

text:
Um, no, this is not how they look like. This is a mathematical model that describes a way to model atoms. Sheesh. I wouldn't say it is better either... it's just a different way to think about models. All of science is a model based on a set up axioms which may or may not be true and which there is no way to prove them because PROOF only a mathematical/logical concept and is only meaningful in a logical system. Everything we do intellectually as humans is based on models we create of the universe.... those models are not real. The only thing that is real is the universe. But as we learn more about the universe using our models we learn our models are not perfect so look for better models... but almost inevitably always think our current model is the actual universe. In fact, it is likely that our models become counterproductive.

I mean, all you are doing is representing points of orbitals with spheres... nothing special and really adds zero to any intellectual understanding and ultimately is just a discretization of space which is quite common to do. After all, every point plot is the same idea. I don't see any real benefit from doing this except that it's cool to see. In fact, I've seen this in papers 50 years old except they were just 2D static black and white plots which almost are likely due to not having sophisticated plotting capabilities.

The point I'm making here is that it isn't a better way... it's the same way. It's like saying a point plot of a line plot is a better way to visualize a line plot and pretend it's some great new discovery. Oh sure, it will bring in the ad revenue so that everyone has to pay more at the store and people that really have no idea of science will thing it is unlocking some secret to the universe but it's really nothing special. Now if they somehow actually offered some insight in to how the internals of atoms really worked(such as if they revealed something new such as how atoms interacted with each other at the sub-atomic level then it might be something useful). Else this is just taking something already well know for many decades and putting a new coat of paint on it and calling it new(which happens to be extremely common but relatively useless because it's mostly hype).

text: Actually, in your most simplistic terms. It's quite easy to picture what an atom looks like. If you think about what is involved in looking at something on a macro level scale, what you see is light reflected off the object. If you could zoom in and see light reflecting off an atom, which isn't possible in the traditional sense, then what you would see is a weird semi-reflective semi translucent cloud. What that cloud looks like would be reflective of its environment and it's structure. How reflective in translucent it would be would be reflective of how many electrons are in those particular orbitals. So in other words, it would be like a fuzzy mirror scattered in a weird cloud. Even in black and white light it would look quite psychedelic. The intensity of the reflected light would be proportional to the probability of an electron being at that location in the cloud. This is something that could actually be rendered by a program. If you had an intense enough laser source, and enough atoms and you were able to correlate the measurements, you could actually generate a probabilistic image of what this would look like. It's basically how they visualized the photon.

text:
Sadly, even these brain-friendly representations are woefully inaccurate. That's because these "visual models" fail to represent 3 important aspects of electrons:

o Physical representation.  As you know, so-called "electrons" are not actually particles in a quantum sense. They're simply a maximum average point of energy in a field of energy that forms the various "cloud" shapes around the nucleus of atoms. So it's a bit like looking at sunlight reflecting off of a surface and asking "where are the particles located?" Or looking at a field pattern of magnetism and asking "where are the particles located?"  It's just too abstract. We may be better off asking: "which point of a reflected surface is measurably the brightest". Or, which spot in a given magnetic field is yields the highest magnetic strength?"  Those questions get a lot closer to what these "electrons" actually represents in their orbital field clouds. So seeing them represented as a moving mass of small particles is not much different than seeing water in an ocean wave represented as a moving mass of individual particles.  Helpful? Maybe.

o Speed.  The speed of a so-called "electron" in its orbital shell or "wave cloud" is not really depicted, other than as a slow moving mass of individual particles. (I believe electron speed was one of the items on your wish list). In reality, the speed of electrons in their orbital shells is close to the speed of light (depending on the medium). Thus, the movement of a so-called "electron" (remember, its just a maximal value in an energy field) is so fast to human perception as to be considered statically "everywhere at once" (much like sunlight). So if you could visualize a beam of sunlight, made up of photons, but shaped like one of these electron cloud formations, then you would be much closer to reality.

o Size.  There is also no sense of proper size or scale of the electron in relation to the 'wave cloud' in which it is shown or the nucleus upon which it orbits. In reality, the size of an electron (average maximal point of energy) is so infinitesimally small in relation to the immense distance between it and the nucleus in the quantum scale. For example, a hydrogen atom consists of a single proton and a single electron. If this single proton was the size of a ping pong ball at the center of the atom, then we the farthest we would expect to find the electron would be about 4,040 ft away (about 13-1/2 football fields away) in its orbital shell.  And since the diameter of an electron is about 1/1000 of a proton, when compare with the scale of the ping pong ball, the size of the electron would be about 1/1000th of 1.5 inches, which is far less than the thickness of a human hair in relation to the ping pong-sized proton to which it orbits.

And look, I get it. You're animated 3D models were shooting for a different way to visualize the standard orbital clouds by bringing them to life.  So its a difficult problem to tackle. But I do applaud your efforts to try to represent something that is mostly conceptual to our human scale macro sensibilities to give it more of a 'tactile feel'.

This video has good simplification of a way to visualize electron orbital clouds:  https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=BPkcDWLBsrI

And I think one of the best representations of atoms, as a group, that I've ever seen was in a 3D visualization of an actual atomic lattice structure. And while that did not attempt to depict the inner structure of an individual atom as you are doing, it did give a very real sense of the way in which atoms bind together to form the basic elements as a 3D rotating lattice stitched together from many images taken from an electron scanning microscope:  https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=yqLlgIaz1L0

The electron orbitals primarily determine the chemical reactions between atoms.

text: Each of these visualizations is intended to represent a single orbital, so there's no jumping involved. In fact, in each of these the position of the electron is undetermined, and what you're seeing are positions where the electron might be found if you look. text: This video shows the correctness of the Madelung-Bohm concept, according to which there are stationary flows of a certain medium inside the atom, and it is the movements of this medium that determine all the macroproperties exhibited by the particles and the atom. In Russia, this concept was developed by Vladimir Atsyukovsky from about the 50s of the 20th century, who came to this independently and only later learned about the work of Madelung. As an engineer, Atsyukovsky in his work encountered a number of inconsistencies between electromagnetic calculations and actual measurement results, and, not satisfied with the assumption of errors that turned out to be too large with fairly accurate and thorough experiments, he began to study the initial work of Maxwell, and then his predecessors and followers. In the process of this study, he came to the conclusion that the rejection of the universal world medium was, at the very least, premature, and the return to it led to the creation of a simple mechanistic model, similar to the one that Madelung got mathematically. At the same time, the application of this model allowed to obtain error-free results in the original work and led to several special experiments showing its validity.

text:
As a computational chemist who spends quite a lot of time working with atomic orbitals, I found this video extremely interesting. I guess that the 3d visuals of balls moving in space are actually quite closely linked to these so-called "fuzzy clouds". In fact, an alternative (stationary) way of representing a fuzzy cloud, is to draw it as a collection of dots, where the density of dots corresponds to the probability of finding an electron at a given location. Here, we've just got 3d balls instead of dots, but other than that it is the same idea.

The fact that the balls are in motion nicely illustrates the idea that when an electron is closer to the nucleus, it is likely to move faster - if the potential energy is more negative, the kinetic energy will be correspondingly more positive. This is in fact why relativistic effects are important in heavier atoms: when the electron is close to the nucleus of a heavy atom, it's speed can approach the speed of light, meaning that classical quantum mechanics breaks down and one needs to use the Dirac equation (or an approximation of it) to correctly describe what's going on.

text:
The polarity of a water molecule is due to the filled electron orbitals in the outer shell.

Water is frequently depicted as H-O-H, and in diagrams the arms are usually bent down, reflecting the reality that the hydrogen atoms are not in fact 180° out of phase with each other, but instead actually about 104°, making a wide triangle.

What these diagrams fail to depict are the filled electron orbitals, which are like two lobes. These are perpendicular to the plane that the hydrogen atoms sit on and bend "up" similar to how the hydrogen atoms bend "down." If you plot the "furthest" parts of the hydrogen atoms and the filled electron orbital lobes as four points in space and connect them, you get a tetrahedron, or a pyramid with a three sided base.

One edge of that tetrahedron will be along the line connecting the two hydrogen atoms, and this "side" of the water molecule is positively charged. Perpendicular to this, and on the furthest edge away on the tetrahedron will be a line connecting the two orbitals, and this side is negatively charged. This distribution of charge is why water is a polar molecule.

This diagram from Wikipedia depicts this phenomenon: https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Sp3_hybridization_of_H2O.jpg
You can see the tetrahedral structure as the little grey pyramid in the center of the 3d model.

Edit: I didn't clearly state this, but it is evident from the model I linked to; the oxygen atom is in the center of the tetrahedron.

text:
In a single bond, two p-orbital lobes overlap strongly and form a sigma bond. In a double bond, a 2nd pair p-orbitals form across the original sigma bond (in this manner 8 三 8), known as a pi bond, but since they do not overlap much, a double bond is only slightly stronger than a single bond. The same goes for triple bond where a second pair of pi bonds form perpendicular to the first pi bond, across the sigma bond.

Only unpaired electrons form bonds as unpaired electrons can only be in one "colour" of the orbital. 
This is called bonding orbitals since paired electrons in phase are of lower energy.
Paired electrons however exist in both colours and the 4 electrons (2 pairs) form both bonding and antibonding orbitals which are of higher energy and unstable.
Of such bonds there are s-p sigma bonds, s-s sigma bonds, and p-p sigma and pi bonds.

Fun fact: Benzene ring electrons are in a giant delocalised pi bond with a wavefunction of a ring above and below the sigma bonds that bond the carbon atoms together.

text: @wangnagene  Bonds are not inherently any more or less "real" than orbitals are.  In fact, bonds ARE orbitals ... they're just molecular orbitals rather than atomic orbitals.  This means they have much more complicated mathematical functions that mostly cannot be solved exactly, but there are programs like Gaussian and GAMESS that approximate the solutions using numerical methods and can be used to generate density maps that look a lot like the images at 0:35-0:40 in the video, and presumably those could be used to produce the same sorts of pictures shown near the end of the video using a more or less identical technique.

text: ​ @wangnagene  A bond is the result of the electric forces and does hold atoms in close proximity to form a new substance. But that bond formation involves changing electrons from being part of the atoms (a single nucleus) to being part of the new substance (a compound with multiple nuclei). The original atomic orbital (wavefunction) is no longer applicable when discussing the bond, so a new molecular orbital (wavefunction) is computed that represents all the characteristics of the electron as part of the compound. Like atomic orbitals, a 3d estimate of how these molecular orbitals "look" can be generated.

text:
@sadman9758 The "dust cloud" you mention is called the electron cloud and it simply is a visual representation of where that ONE single elctron could be. Its moving CRAZY fast (has momentum) all the time and because of some guy named Heisenberg, we can't know where the electron is AND its momentum at the same time. So instead, we describe where the electron is more likely to be. Thats the cloud. 

Tl;dr: The cloud is just a bajillion possible places that the ONE electron could move to.

text:
Imagine in a single bond you have two atoms.

1 electron from one atom is moving in a sideways figure 8 or infinity symbol, towards the other atom and then back on itself, the other electron is constantly directly opposite and anti the other electron.

Imagine both electrons are trailing a rope made of pure negative charge, both loops of the path (both circles of the figure 8) are looped around the positive charge at the centre of each  atoms. The rope is pulled taught at both ends by this attraction and thus a bond is formed.


If you can picture this as a single covalent bond then you can extrapolate that double and triple bonds are just more crowded paths with thicker and tighter rope.

Single bonds are not limited to just two atoms. Methane, for example, has four single bonds formed with five atoms. Typical diagrams will illustrate the hybrid orbitals as symmtric lobes and the hydrogens as localized globes. text: Hey so the “bonds” you are speaking of are not really lines connecting orbitals. There are two types of bonds, sigma bonds, and pi bonds. Sigma bonds arise when two orbitals directly overlap with each other, while pi bonds arise when two orbitals are parallel to each other. A double bond is a combination of one sigma bond and one pi bond. I did create a 3D model of these bonds, but unfortunately, it wasn’t a dynamic visualization (because I am dumb). I’d be happy to share it with you if you are interested.

text: Love the video, the images and visual models of atomics are absolutely stunning. You definitely made a model that is interesting and dynamic as compared to the traditional ones. text: @Jono98806  Actually no -- the constituents of protons and neutrons are highly relativistic quarks and gluons so nonrelativistic quantum mechanics is a very poor approximation, and Bohmian mechanics only makes any sense for nonrelativistic QM (to whatever unclear extent that's being used in this visualization, which clearly disagrees with it because bohmian particles are supposed to be stationary in energy eigenstates). You might be able to visualize hadrons made from heavier quarks, like the J/psi.
author: @isodoublet

text: @isodoublet  I think this video was about visualisations of electron orbitals of atoms and the original commenter was interested in similar visualisations of subatomic particles like protons or neutrons. There was no mention of Bohmian mechanics or whether it's relativistic or non-relativistic (though these electron orbitals are solutions of the non-relativistic Shcroedinger equation, I'll grant that).
author: @Jono98806

text: ​ @Jono98806  I know what the video was about and what the commenters asked. The video states that the visualization is based on Bohmian trajectories. The claim is dubious, since there'd be no rotation if that were the case, but at any rate the claim was made, and because of the fundamental incompatibility between Bohmian mechanics and special relativity, the visualization wouldn't work for a proton or a neutron. Also, protons and neutrons are each made of three (valence) quarks, which means the configuration space is 9-dimensional and so this visualization would also be 9-dimensional.

Keep strong. Dont forget that despite the struggles and madness in this world today, God is full of justice, mercy and love. 
Justice said we broke His perfect law - causing the world's previous perfection to be
destroyed - and therefore we deserve Hell (like a punishment in any legal system but this is eternal as His perfect law is eternal too). Don't think you fit in that category? Ever done one of these?: lying, stealing - regardless of how small the object EVER, hating others - which is murder in God's perfect law, lusting (plus God sees our entire thought life). Justice says "the soul that sins shall die" - if we break one in thought/word/deed it's as if we're guilty of all of them. Quite simply, living by the law (which is doing everything perfectly) is impossible for sinful humans 

. The law shows us that 1. We will die in Hell if we fail to follow it and 2. We cannot save ourselves BUT, 3. God's perfect, immovable law points us to Christ, who followed and fulfilled the law in thought, word and deed perfectly in our place. He did what we couldn't and did it on our behalf. He was then sentenced to death on a cross, and took our personal punishment for our sin, paying our penalty (like paying our fine) completely FOR us, and has given us freedom. 

If we turn from the sins we have committed and repent (pursue the opposite direction of love through Christ) He will, overtime, recreate us back into that previously perfect image through The Holy Spirit which Jesus sends to all who accept Him as their personal Lord and Savior of their life. He will help us through the struggle, the stress, and anything we experience in the world. It's about letting Christ in to guide and teach you and obeying Him through His power (not ourselves, we need Him to help us as it's impossible without depending on His power and instruction). 

He is our substitute in His life, death and resurrection. He essentially rewrote history in our place so that, if you believe in Him, it will be as if you had never sinned if you accept Christ's death as our own in our place. 

He is in Heaven right now preparing a place for us so that He can take His faithful, believing children home with Him when He returns. He will ressurrect us from death when He returns, giving mercy to those who accept His love, instruction and teachings in their life, and give justice to those who refuse it. 

He doesn't want ANY of us to go to Hell and die for continuing in evil and rejecting His way to life, thats why He died FOR us. Hes giving EVERYONE a chance, He wants everyone to take the free gift of salvation from Hell. He wants us to be His and begin to follow His life of love and service through His power and abiding (staying) with Him. So long as we keep our hearts near to Christ through His strength, strive to follow His will of perfect love revealed in the Bible, and let Him lead in the midst of (very certain) pitfalls and struggles, we will, in time, win the ultimate victory over sin, pain and DEATH through Christ. Even if you are willing to be made willing, pray for Jesus to come in and He will do what we can't. Give us The Holy Spirit who will guide us in the right way. 

Christ says in John 16:33: I have told you these things, so that in Me you may have [perfect] peace. In the world you have tribulation and distress and suffering, but be courageous [be confident, be undaunted, be filled with joy]; I have overcome the world.” [My conquest is accomplished, My victory abiding.]
-  (AMPLIFIED version) 

NOTE: You are NEVER too sinful or messed up that God cannot turn your life around through Jesus. EVER. Regardless of what you've done or what you're going through you CAN make it through Jesus. X

@declankelly9350  well that's true, ask my wife... but really there is not much that's attracts me to the status quo.
And further, I learned over 67 years that when authorities (governments, universities corporations, medical monopolies etc) promote anything with gusto, they are invariably pushing a narrative that is intended to propagandize their captive audience.  Brainwashing is what it is.

So after years of poking at EInstein's theories, with a stick of suspicion, it became crystal clear that the theory is dead.  It was always set up from the start to be a exciting story that as Nikola Tesla described, " is a magnificent mathematical garb which fascinates, dazzles and makes people blind to the underlying errors."

And if you can review it with a critical eye, then its not even hard to find where the errors lie.

The same motives that require deceptions are at the heart of all government and authoritarian  narratives, such as pandemics, wars, economies, science, medicine, history, geology, astronomy, entertainment, music, everything has been corrupted by those whose aim is total control.

Meantime I'm happy to discuss details about where Einstein is wrong, details that I learned from smart men, nothing I discovered myself.

When a dumbbell shell is depicted for one electron, we don't know anything about the electron trajectory. All we know is the electron can be anywhere on that dumbbell-shaped shell. It's like a double-slit experiment when one electron kinda passes through two holes at the same time :) That's fascinating. I mean how it behaves like a wave and a particle, all rolled into one. Truth be told, we still don't have full understanding of the logic/theory behind but we have some hypothetical theories (String theory, etc.) that seemed to be really wrong or way too flawed. That looks like too advanced, too sophisticated a question to solve, i.e. like asking cave people of 100,000 years ago to calculate spaceship trajectories accounting for relativistic effect of acceleration or deceleration of time (and things like that). I don't think people will find the answers for that within the next 100-200 years. Progress and science have slowed down recently. We are now already moving very slowly in terms of progress and science. I would not expect answers too such advanced problems. It would be easier to find cure for cancer, etc. It would be easier to launch a small ship to a nearby star. We have to appreciate all that has been achieved by scientists. Just an opinion.
author: @billmorrigan386

text: These balloon shaped patterns are the spherical geometry equivalent of standing waves. They're not even specific to QM, in fact. The reason they show up is that the hydrogen atom is spherically symmetric, so it is convenient to write orbitals in terms of structures that behave in a nice useful way under rotations. This is described by group theory so it can get a little involved, but the moral of the story is that what's being plotted are solutions of well-defined angular momentum (as well defined as can be in quantum mechanics, anyway, which usually means specifying the magnitude of the angular momentum vector as well as its projection along the z axis).

author: @AdrianLParker

text:
Bohr's postulates :
1. Electrons revolve around the nucleus in circular paths
2. The electrons revolve in a energy shells or orbits named as K, L, M, N.. or numbered 1, 2, 3, ...
3. Electrons, when they revolve neither lose nor gain energy, hence the orbits are also called stationary orbits.
4. Electrons revolve in the orbits with a certain angular momentum(product of moment of inertia and angular velocity), this angular momentum is always an integral multiple of h/2pi.

L = nh/2pi

n = principal quantum number
h = planck's constant
L = angular momentum
5. Electrons release energy as they jump to higher orbits and absorb it as they jump to lower orbits.
The absorbed or released energy is given by dE = E2 - E1 = hv.

v = nu

6. As the value of "n" increases the size and energy of the orbit increases.

text: Sorry but 0:40 and 4:09 (versions of the electron cloud) are bad representations.  All they convey is what a probability pattern looks like visually - an actual atom "looks" nothing like an electron cloud.  The TRUE representation of the atom is the traditional nucleus with single point electrons surrounding it.   The electron cloud concept is still useful because it gives a different view (and different information), but let's not confuse probability with actuality.

text: As cool as those are, they don't show the reality. Yes, you can represent excited states for the hydrogen atom and other orbitals with different quantum numbers, but since we're talking about a hydrogen atom, it only has one electron, and thus only one orbital can exhist when you excite the electron, and are accurately represented here. But in every other element, more than one orbital exhist at the same time. How does that complex sum of orbitals adds up to a real atom with more than one electron? What are their sizes relative to one other? Do they overlap in any way? I know the wave function shapes are obtained by calculation for the hydrogen atom and multi-electron atoms are nearly impossible to calculate, but to this day I haven't found a decent explanation or depiction of the image that multi-electron atoms would generate, accounting all its orbitals exhisting at the same time.

text:
Totally agree. If the purpose of the image is to convey the reality of the atom, then I think these are very misleading. 

What’s missing for me are the elements of time and probability. When animated, all those dots give the impression of buhzillions of electrons orbiting all at once, not probable locations of one electron in each orbit.

I suspect these would work better using the “mist” approach as suggested, but with the added feature of a “snapshot” mode that represents an actual measurement of a specific electron. In other words, you see the vague mist until you hit the “measure” button, then the orbital that you are measuring freezes and the mist condenses down into a single point. You could freeze one orbital at a time, leaving the rest as probability mists, or freeze the lot and see each wave collapsed into its measured point. Every time you measure, you could get a point in a different location within the probability wave.

Admittedly, tough to turn into a static graphic, but then that’s just the nature of the atomic beast.

Electrons don't 'move' around the atom with a fixed speed like that, it is a wavefunction more accurately depicted by a vibrating drum with a fixed orientation. This is going to confuse people alllll over again.

text: An electron is "guided" by an electromagnetic field. Nothing more, nothing less. It is not guided by any "wave." If it were, then this alleged "wave field" would be a new force field acting on the electron. The "wave field" is a mathematical construct to describe its probabilistic behavior, which is caused by real forces (gravity, electromagnetism, etc).

text: Yes, he can, and it would be even more wrong because now he would superimpose classical images of wave functions on top of each other, even though the physics doesn't work at all like that. What causes the electronic configurations of atoms and molecules is the Pauli exclusion principle, or, more precisely, the relativistic effect that fermionic wave functions have to be anti-symmetric. The problem with multi-quanta systems is that humans can not actually visualize the phase space. Its dimensions are too high. So what we do in textbooks is to usually artificially separate that which in nature is actually inseparable. We may feel good about it, but it is utterly incorrect.

text: In simple terms it's the uncertainty principle. Trying to localize the electronic wavefunction around the nucleus leads to a momentum uncertainty, which counterbalances the effect of that electrostatic attraction. Nature "does not like to be compressed", if you will. The notion that the electron has a location is wrong for the same reason. In that case we are trying to pretend that we can keep an electron field localized to a single point, which would lead to an infinite momentum and hence energy uncertainty. The physical "reality" is that the system is always a continuous field. It's just not a classical field with an electric charge and a magnetic dipole distribution but a quantum field... and that, unfortunately, is not something that the human mind can easily visualize.

text: In terms of mass density atoms are mostly "empty". Nuclei contain almost all of the mass-energy. A hydrogen atom is about 120pm in radius. A classical proton charge radius can be estimated at 0.8fm. This means that the proton is roughly 100,000 times smaller than a hydrogen atom. That gives a ratio of approx. 15 orders of magnitude between the proton's classical energy density and that of the hydrogen atom. Take these classical back-of-the-envelope calculations with a grain of salt. It doesn't really work this way. In actual interactions these systems cause scattering that is highly energy dependent, hence it doesn't really make sense to assign these coarse classical densities to them. Their effective "size" (cross section) depends on how they interact.

text: Yes, totally agree

Electrons move really fast, but they do not "orbit" the nucleus at the speed of light. Only massless particles like photons are permitted to move at c . Electrons can be perceived as a wave-function until it interacts with another particle, then it collapses into a particle. You can calculate the position or momentum of an electron but not both. As such, the peak of the wave-function implies where the electron is most likely to be because you must remember that as a wave function, the electron can exist at any of those points. Particles are difficult to observe not just due to their speed but also size. Protons/Neutrons have approx 1,836x the mass of an electron. They're considered point particles for this very reason, lol.

text: I do not believe that an electron or other subatomic "particles" exist as BB-like or marble-like dots or spheres flying in or around an atom. Rather, the "particle" is a region of space-time that is energetically different than the surrounding space-time and, to the outside observer, has an orbital shape. The orbital shape is the shape of the electron's space-time and so the orbital shape is the shape of the electron. The orbital is NOT a shaped volume of space where a discrete particle might probabalistically be found. The quantum of energy that is the electron is shape-shifting. The electron changes shape.

text:
My twopenn'orth. IMO Trying to imagine what things 'look like' in the limit of modern physics is counter-productive. We have evolved to think about the world in certain ways because of the way our bodies interact with the world. We imagine things to be 'particles' because we understand how stones (and apples) behave. We can grasp the idea of 'waves' too because we experience such things commonly. But when we have to deal with the particle-wave duality our brains can't cope. We have no referent.
The same is true of space time. We think we have a grasp of space, time and gravity - but the twists and turns of 4 dimensional spacetime in a gravitational field is impossible for us to grasp in any intuitive sense.
I think most physicists these days have had to admit to themselves that trying to create mental images of reality outside of our own domain inevitably leads to error and misunderstanding. It's not just unhelpful, it's harmful. The best we can do is to use symbolism, that is mathematics. Just trust that and let go of the 'need to know'.

text:
People just need to accept, as a premise, that atoms cannot be seen or visualized like that. These are very cool depictions and they are probably the best animations I've every seen, but it is physics, not reality.
Usually, teachers and people say that we want to see a single electron in a certain position, orbiting in some way around the proton, and that is  wrong because "the truth is that the electron position is a continuous superposition of many positions". However, I think they are wrong when they jump to the conclusion that, in reality, the electron is actually in all those places at the same time (or, at least, with a certain probability density). This is all math, don't  forget, it doesn't actually translates in an ontological fact. The physics and math kinda works (quantum mechanics is a very successful theory, but it is far from perfect) but it is just a thing that we constructed utilizing models and ideas. And I think that's probably the real beauty of science.

text:
I am not sure I would have the electrons orbiting in these diagrams. There is actually no way to know for certain how electrons move within an orbital, but we do know they do not move in classical orbits. Since this is accelerated motion orbits would have to be faster than the speed of light (not allowed) or they would decay and crash into the nucleus. In some respect it is probably better to imagine the electrons randomly popping from location to location within the orbital without crossing the distance via something like tunneling. They may not do that either, but it is better than having orbits in my opinion. 

If I were to rewrite the animation I would have one (or two, if it is a filled orbital) solid electron moving location according to the probabilities of the orbital, and it would have a fading "tail" for previous locations. With the right fade-out you would get a shadow image that roughly matched the electron density of the orbital as the electron moved within it. That would be much more accurate.

text: @lunkel8108  They are the funny shapes shown around an atom in which you may or may not find an electron.
author: @TonOfHam

text:
@TonOfHam  Right, the areas with high probability density. And it's not like there really is a point-like electron hiding somewhere in there and we just don't know where exactly; the underlying wavefunction is the electron. And as you can see in the video, those fill out the atoms pretty well. That's why I commonly see people taking issue with the "99% empty" statement, it's far more evocative of the Bohr model with a little dot flying around in a circle.
And when we say "what does an atom look like" we don't mean how it interacts with visible light or something but rather what its (electronic) structure is. And atomic and molecular orbitals are the answer to that. Nobody's trying to fool anybody.
author: @lunkel8108

text: @lunkel8108  If you want to call orbitals an image that's fine, it technically meets the description. I'm just tire of people saying they can "see atoms" when that is not what is happening.

text: These orbitals are only what you would get if you made a measurement with some preferred orientation (they are eigenfunctions). In reality the electron will typically be in a superposition of many states, and when you make a measurement you force the wave function to collapse to one of these eigenfunction orbitals. In other words, those strange donut shaped will align themselves to your measurement coordinate system.

text:
I wouldn't go too far as to say that this is what particles look like. The best way to think about particles is that they are excitations of a field...like a vortex in a pool of water or a cloud in the sky...they are objects that have some kind of permeance that go along with consistent properties, until they bump into something else, an interaction occurs and then those properties change because of that interaction.

Now...this is just an opinion because its not proven, but there are scientists that believe that the standard model is not fundamental. And If you asked me what I think a particle would look like based on what scientists are currently looking into, it would look look like this : https://biocomplexity(dot)indiana(dot)edu/research/bionet/images/figiv_1(dot)gif
^^^ replace the (dot) with an actual dot (.)

However, this series of connections between nodes isn't "visible" in the sense that you can actually see it look like this. That network is invisible because it has no notion of "light" because it's smaller than a photon. Even more is that, such a thing exists in a much larger network of fields...so you can imagine that a particle looks like a very tight spider web in a much larger cosmic sized spider web. 

This render minute physics has is more or less a render of the ignorance of the standard model and quantum mechanics, which describes uncertainty in particles because of the inability to measure them with anything smaller than other particles. Even with soft detection, you need to use statistics...this model is exactly what that is...a statistical discrete model of our ignorance for where the particle is.

text:
You are close--it is related. But there's more to it.
An atom like oxygen has several electrons in it, and not all of them can occupy the ground state orbital--only a single electron can occupy a given quantum state, but the electron has two possible spin states, so every spatial wave function configuration as pictured here can hold exactly two electrons, with opposite spins. So if there are more than two, they "pile up" such that some are in more complicated orbital states.
Now, on top of that, those states could be quantum superpositions of different ones pictured here, which alters their shape.
And in a covalent bond which joins two atoms, it's more complicated still, because there, some of the outermost electrons will be in a quantum superposition of being in one atom or the other atom! And if the resulting wave function has a large cloud of probability in between the two atomic nuclei, that will tend to electrostatically hold the atoms together. It's a chemical bond.
If you were to create an animation like this for the bonding electrons in a molecule, it would show fuzzy clouds of probability floating in between the atomic nuclei. The shapes become altered from the ones you'd see for a single atom standing alone, to a more holistic picture. And there are more complicated things that happen--shapes like the benzene ring where some electrons are in donut-shaped clouds smeared out over the whole ring, and metals where some electrons are delocalized over the whole structure which means they can conduct electricity.

text: No, it's not. An electron doesn't have a size. The real problem isn't with the graphics, though. The real problem is that the Schroedinger equation is NOT the correct physical model for what is going on in atomic physics. It assumes that there is a classical potential, but no such thing exists. In reality the electron interacts with the charge of the nucleon trough virtual photons, i.e. if you wanted to understand the actual dynamical physical process, you would have to do a quantum-electrodynamics calculation. That, unfortunately, opens the can of an infinite number of degrees of freedom, which can not be visualized. What physicists do, instead, is to decompose the process into an infinite series of Feynman diagrams, which then can be sorted by their relevance for the observed phenomena. What you are seeing here is really an oversimplified picture taken too far. You might as well do Bohr's model of the atom with Kepler style orbits. It's about as accurate as this visualization.

text: At no size. Absolutely everything you see is the result of quantum behavior. The mere fact that there are atoms can not be reduced to classical physics, already. One can construct a "transition" from quantum physics to classical physics trough what is called Rydberg atoms, but one has to work really hard to do that and these are artificial systems. The actual physical mechanism that leads to "classical observations" comes from continuous weak measurements, something that was first understood in 1929, but that has mostly been ignored in mainstream physics education because in order to understand it one has to understand quantum mechanics first. It's kind of hard to teach QM by requiring that the student understands QM, already, so we don't start with that (even though nature does). The problem is that most people never get to the advanced ideas that are underlying continuous weak measurement, so they are stuck with false ideas about what is and is not quantum mechanical. It's an educational problem, not a physical one. I can't tell you how to solve it... I don't have a recipe to cut this Gordian Knot, either.

text: I really like your stuff and though I commend your effort to make a better atomic model graphically, and I agree these renders are pretty. However, how are they really different from traditional atomic orbital (AOs) diagrams which have orbital probability clouds (s, p, d, f) ? I understand that might be confusing that traditional AO boundaries are confidence intervals, and that the distribution is not heterogeneous at all radii within those clouds and you would like to look "inside that boundary. However, your model which uses the discretization of space as dots which visually says "position" but is actually probability and taking what visually says "trajectory" or "velocity"  and making it mean flow of Psi, feel like non-intuitive trade offs to me. Traditional AO diagrams which uses color to define probability and are cross-sectional achieve the same thing you show but are continuous and avoid confusion of probability with actual position.

text:
I think "really what it looks like" isn't possible, because the electron is not a point particle and it's wave packet is 'spread out' before it's measured, but the wave packet is just a device for interpreting the probability of position/momentum when it is measured.  So it's not a particle, it's not a wave, when it becomes entangled with your measurement apparatus is when you can sort of "conjure" it (although that makes it sound like it didn't exist before.. it did we just can't see it).  I think the model in this video tells us the most we can know. 

A related question is, can you say anything objectively "is a thing" until something interacts with it?  We define everything by our observations, and those observations come from interaction.. and similarly interaction -> entanglement -> reducing the range of possibility (uncertainly/standard deviation) for the object.  The fact that we see the "same thing" every time we or anyone else interacts just tells us that, within some range of possibility, it has some observable properties when interacted with.  It's just that electrons and quantum particles really take this to the next level, because they are so tiny and their probability wave has such a large standard deviation.  The variation is outcomes is much larger and more distinct, as we see in things like the double-slit experiment.  It's like, a cat we call gray might range in a tiny frequency of color based on absorbed energy from light, but an electron might go from blue to green (just an analogy).  The variation is so much bigger we start to really see that it's an extreme example of how nothing is precisely determined or known.

The renders look very nice indeed, but I think by building them with visible dots (or particles) pulls them away from their reality - being waves.
If you want to present them this way I would go and reduce their size to the smallest pixel possible - to the level that human eyes can't distinguish them from one another (but can still distinguish the more and less dense areas).
Imho the discreetness is the separation between the different areas of electron "orbitals" (ie the empty zones) are the areas of destructive interference, and the dense areas are the constructive interference (but not separation between pixels in more or less homogeneous area of high "probability").
(Might want to check De Broglie electron model to get better grasp of the core idea)

text:
Science guy here. There are different kinds of observations; that's crucial. You can observe it as a wave (measuring its phase or momentum), and then it looks like a wave, and the question is "what will its phase or momentum be?" Or you can observe it as a point-particle (measuring its position), and then it looks like a point-particle, and the question is "what will its position be?"

(The misleading popularized idea of "measure it and then it collapses", which comes from Max Born, has emphasized measurement of position as the only kind of "measurement" to think about when discussing this area of science: you measure the position, and then it has a position. He ought to have equally emphasized the other half: you can measure the momentum, and then it has a momentum. It is "misleading" because it disregards the complete symmetry (or "duality" as in Boolean algebra) between position and momentum: take any scenario and any true sentence about the scenario, and switch the words "position" and "momentum" and you get another sentence that is also true.)

It is rare that anything in nature (or in artifice!) would measure the position of an electron in an atom.
author: @rodschmidt8952

text:
This would be good for an experiment in which you were planning to observe or measure the position.

I MIGHT go along with a variation of this idea: the highlighting switches rapidly from one dot (or "point-particle") to another, randomly.

(I say "point-particle" because we are talking about a particular shape. The word "particle" also refers to electrons, protons, etc., regardless of shape, so it's ambiguous; is an electron still a "particle" when it's wave-shaped?)
author: @rodschmidt8952

text:
@DarkMoonDroid  The quantum pioneers backed away from the idea of asking "what is it really?" in favor of asking "if we were to observe it, what would we see?"

This is because observation is real, but our ideas of "what is really there" are conclusions that we draw in your heads and they might be wrong; and our conclusions based on daily life, as applied to the quantum realm, ARE wrong.
author: @rodschmidt8952

text:
@dimasgomez  The observation does not make the electron, or anything about it, "become real." It changes the shape. Measure its position, and it will have a position (for a while, anyway). Measure instead its momentum, and it will have a momentum (while being spread out position-wise). 

Max Born wrote about only one half of this, and so the symmetry between position and momentum did not make it into the popularized idea.

author: @Dejawolfs

text:
Yeah my only issue with the video is that it gives the appearance that an electron is a dot / point somewhere in this region of that small size.  But until it is measured, it is not that. In fact, before it's measured, we can't really say anything except what it's wave function tells us about the probability of what we will see when it is measured.  

Now, I think it's also fair to say "the cat isn't there until we've looked at it", in the sense that although we know the cat exists, it is also lying as a wave with (MUCH MUCH smaller) range if possibility / indeterminism until we've seen it, and then it still has a very TINY TINY band in which it is indeterminate (thanks uncertainty principle) in momentum, position, time, energy. 

So the point is that although we can't be exact about anything, before we measure an electron we really can't be very exact at all, and to suggest it exists as a point while it is in that indeterminate state is misleading.. although it may be a good starting point to grasping the sense of the wave of possibility, which is the closest the universe comes to allowing us to understanding it.  

I always think of Kurt Godel incompleteness when I think of electrons. They both tell us about the limits that the universe imposes on our ability to pin it down.

text:
Very Nice for using de Broglie-Bohm formulation! 
But I would describe the wave-particle concept in pilot-wave, and a wave and its peaks as the particles - I mean technically the "speck" is the stuff of electron wave in a most general sense, right?
I mean there's no need for a physical objectification, when the peaks are all we need.
Think about it this way - we have some very advanced instruments for detection of elementary particles, but they're not absolutely perfect, they have (generally speaking) "sensitivity".
Ie if electrons are waves (which we know they are at least sometimes) then it's possible that sometimes (or somewhere) they're just the tiniest waves on the "surface" of the EM field, so tiny that are below our instruments' detection capability. But as all waves they can interfere constructively and sublimate in these places reaching levels we can easily detect ... and Bam - we say - There! It's a particle!
My point is our whole measurement instruments are basically filters, that filter out waves with amplitudes lower than our instruments' sensitivity, and we only see the peaks above that sensitivity level ... completely unaware of the waves and events under that threshold.
To actually see that concept (if haven't imagined it well already) google "FloWave Ocean Energy Research Facility" or another similar wave-laboratory, and you can see how the tiniest of waves can produce a peak of water (or generally speaking energy) that's many, many times higher.

Imho de Broglie-Bohm pilot theory is the most underrated theory ever!
It solves so many problems, and helps you preserve your sanity! (well ... sure you have to give up some comforts like Locality, but I'm actually intrigued by that)

The best we can hope for is you drawing us pretty animated pictures of probability density. That's cool and all, but it still doesn't really help our brains visualise an atom, because it can't be visualised by brains that evolved swinging from trees and walking the prairies of planet Earth.
