text: 0:48 Electrons don't orbit the nucleus. If they did they would slowly lose energy and collapse into the nucleus.  I know you mention Bohmian Trajectories so you know the jury is still out. What we perceive as electrons only exist when the wave function collapses to a point in 3 dimensions. And it's still debatable whether the location of the 3d electron is dependent upon the viewer not the electron. In other words an electron is a standing wave and it's area extends off to infinity. That's how just one particle can interfere with itself in the double slit experiment. Just one "electron" is big enough to span the gap between the slits. You could argue depicting an electron in 3D is to misrepresent what an electron actually is. We as humans simply can't perceive what they truly are. I guess what I'm driving at is restricting an electron to 3 dimensions is hiding the fact quantum entangled particles occupying some higher dimension can extend far beyond even a 3D orbital "cloud". It's entirely possible you would need a computer screen the width of the universe to truly represent what an electron really is. Perhaps there is just one "electron", i.e. an electron field. To represent it in 3d is to hide what it is.

text: And that is where you are wrong! What does an atom looks like? It looks like it’s interaction. Spacetime is a reference frame describing interactions, not an observable. The only observable is the interactions. So yes your images are very nice (indeed very nice) but show you do not understand matter-spacetime. If you can show the image without imposing your classic view of space and time then you will approach understanding. For example, you show your system of coordinates as fixed around a point. That has no sense. Since this is where you have a all different system which is the source of the interactions creating the orbitals, the nucleus. How would you depict it in your view of the atom? First you would need to change the scale and that is because the nuclear force is much much stronger than the electromagnetic force. This is the real meaning of the scale. Geometry is not geometry it is dynamics.

text:
Science Revolution  How can you publish such nonsense? The whole point of quantum mechanics is to describe how particles move in the very tiny regime. They don't follow your commonsense physics because that does not describe the tiny regime at all. The nucleus and the electrons of an atom DO NOT act like a miniature solar system with gravity changed to Coulumb attraction. NO. Study some physics or watch some videos here to understand what is actually observed in the tiny regime. It's one small corner of the wonderful knowledge that is QM.

As for hard atoms, they don't exist. Not fact. What does exist is the repulsion between atoms generated by the outermost electron orbitals. The strength of the repulsion more or less scales up as hardness (complicated, though by the bonds that make up crystals).

text:
Sorry but you just did some nice plots of the orbitals. As a physicist, you must know that under a central force the probability of finding an electron at a given radius from the nucleus is the same, regardless the angular coordinates. In other words, any  isolated atom has spherical symmetry.  It looks like this https://ars.els-cdn.com/content/image/1-s2.0-S000926140901015X-gr1.jpg
The different colors correspond to the electron shells. The quantity depicted is a lower bound to the momentum of the electron, which is maximum at the nucleus. In atomic units, the velocity at the nucleus is equivalent to the atomic number, v=Z thanks to Kato's cusp theorem.
https://doi.org/10.1016/j.cplett.2009.08.034

text:
-The individual dots are the specks he mentions at 2:02, its where an electron might possibly be if you were to observe it. Each observation would give youa  different dot, and if you kept observing it a million times you'd get each of those dots.
- I assume you mean surface of the ball? The ball is a visual representation, in reality it would be a cloud of infinitismally small dots, but the computer cant render that
- what binds them together is the fact that the electron wants to be closer to the nucleus of the atom, so roughly speaking the electromagnetic force.
- again, as he mentions a couple of times, each ball is not a particle. It is the representation of the fact that electrons in reality go around an atom as a probability cloud, not as a single orbting dot as in the traditional classical cartoons of atoms (again, see 2:02 for the analogy). The eletron is the WHOLE set of dots (or at least, where it might be)
- again, there are no individual balls really, its all one electron
- non of the balls are neutrons, none of the balls are protons, they are each, collectively, one electron

I hope that helps

text: The wave function doesn't have a physical meaning, it's just a mathematical tool. What has meaning is its "squared" value at each point in space, which is just the probability of finding the electron at that particular point in space, and thus gains physical meaning. In the video the local "density" of the balls in the animations is a representation of this probability density.

text: This is wrong. There are no "electrons" as particles until the wave function collapses. Before that, there's only a probability function. These images, which seem to depict electrons in specific places, conflate the notion of probability (of the electrons ending up in specific places when the wave function collapses) with the ensuing result of the wave function collapsing. The real problem here is probability - it's seemless. There are no specific points in probability. The traditional shapes are more realistic.

text: Electrons are constantly trying to get away from the atom.  There are no "opposites attract" or "mystery energy" keeping the electron and proton separate.  The proton constantly reacts to the electron trying to escape which it why the electron has a jagged, rough orbit.  Electron Orbitals prove it.  Electrons flow smoothest in a straight line at its own speed. However, when electrons are forced to accelerate, electromagnetism occurs.  Similarly, when Electrons orbitals are pushed closer to the proton due to an overload of neutrons, radiation occurs since the electrons have to exert more power to try to escape. (Uranium)....but all this is just a theory of mine....I remember getting a bunch of D's in Physics classes.

text:
Looks like an advanced hard drive to me, esp. since information has been encoded in the quantum phase of an electron with a high speed laser (Ahn, Weinacht, Bucksbaum) in 2000. But since all focus is on statistics by way of probabilities and uncertainties, it's not highly probable that any scientist will try to look for the information encoded in the hard drive. It seems more important to feel proud about a statistical model. Or maybe (lack of) imagination is the problem, which is more important than knowledge, I've heard somewhere...

In any case, a paradigm shift is needed, because if the information storage theory is true, what we're doing currently with atoms is like listening to the mobile phone frequency bands, but only focusing on the spectrum image, not the calls themselves. And even worse, destroying an information-packed atom would be like burning a book.

text:
This representation jives with my understanding, or rather, understood inevitable misunderstanding, of electron positions. Ever since I "grew out of" the orbital model, I just imagined the nucleus in a defined position and the electrons in a cloud of "I have no idea" that reflects either the state of our current measurement capabilities (after all, if we don't care at all about momentum, we can at least potentially zero in on the position of everything in an atom for one instant), the unshakeable uncertainty regarding electron positions, or all the potential locations of the electron in an atom. Essentially, I see it as both a cloud and shell of potential locations, rather than any defined orbit.

Also, holy crap that must've eaten a lot of RAM to render. Props to your dedication to visualizing electron clouds, and your rendering horsepower.

text: The electron's position is not super finite. You just have the highest probability of finding it at specific locations which are based on the principle quantum number and the azimuthal quantum number.
author: @lorddonk9806

text: Butwhy  for all intents and purposes (ie. assuming that calculus works for distances), an electron can exist at an infinite number of positions, since an infinite number of points exist in any space of non-zero measure. However, this infinity is an 'uncountable' infinity (kind of like a smooth gradient) whereas the infinity of energy states, which correspond to the probabilities of finding the electron at a given point in space, is 'countable' (like a staircase).
author: @rufusstanier8893

text: Butwhy  the position CAN be narrowed down to a pretty precise point, but then its momentum would be highly uncertain because the high frequency of the wave that would be used to ascertain the position of the electron could give the electron a very fierce bump into some uncertain direction at high velocity.
author: @AkamiChannel

text: @rufusstanier8893  I'm not sure if physicists think that. Some definitely have the view that space and time itself are quantized and so it would not be an uncountable infinity.
author: @AkamiChannel

text: A way I like to think of it (but which is itself a possibly inaccurate oversimplification) is that if two parallel universes are identical in every way except for the position of a quantum particle (like an electron) the two parallel universes are the same universe, with there being an x% chance of it being one or the other.  With <crazy experiments> this can be somewhat observed to be true, with the electron being at all possible positions "at once" in some circumstances.  But, if you "measure" the exact position of an electron, it can only be in one spot at once, so now the x% of being in any universe where the electron was in any other position drops to 0%, for the moment of the measurement.

text: @AkamiChannel  that’s why I said ‘for all intents and purposes’. The fact remains that the mathematical basis for quantum physics at this scale (which allows for extremely accurate predictions of nature) relies on calculus, which in turn relies on the fact that space and time are smooth. Although quantisation of space-time is necessary for theories of quantum gravity, no one knows for sure how it works yet, and at these length scales the effect of any quantisation of position is minuscule compared to the effect of the quantisation of energy states of a bound electron, so I think it’s still a very reasonable approximation to make, especially when it comes to explaining qualitatively how most physicists will think about this stuff when they’re actually doing physics.

text:
@terryfuldsgaming7995 

 A particle has some aspects of a wave and some aspects like a marble, but it is its own thing that acts in a way not quite like either of them. Like a marble, it exists in discrete indivisible integer amounts. There is never two and a half electrons. Like a wave, it can vibrate, change shape, and flow. The position of a particle is not a single point in space, but something called the "position distribution". You can imagine it as a cloud which is heavier in some places than others. And you can imagine that weight as how "likely" you are to "find the particle" in that exact spot if you look, or as "how much of" the particle is there, or as "how much" the particle "is" there as opposed to somewhere else.

 I know that doesn't sound very exact right now, but the physics acts on the shape and strength of that cloud as a whole as if it were one individual marble with that strange shape. Even if two halves of the cloud aren't physically connected in space anymore because you waved your hand through the middle and split it in two. There are a lot of experiments that pull that stunt of splitting the cloud in two, and sometimes that can make it look like the particle is teleporting, because one time we'll look and "find it" in one half of the cloud, and another time we'll look and "find it" in the other half. But it's not actually teleporting, it just looks that way. Scientists don't want it to sound like it's teleporting, but humans have monkey brains who see two separate smaller rocks, instead of only one rock of the same size that's still just one rock even though the two sides aren't touching anymore. The position distribution is the real shape of it and like a single marble we see it only once and in only one place each time we look, so of course if the cloud is split in two we can't ever see it in both places at the same time nor in neither.

 For small objects, this effect can be very powerful, letting electrons have shapes that straddle two nearby wires in a transistor or SSD card and store information super dense on your thumbdrive. But the strength of that effect falls off the larger something is and the more particles are in it. So in some tiny sense, a very thin wisp of you too small to matter even on a subatomic scale does extend all the way to to store, just like in some tiny way your own personal gravity affects the shape of the moon ever so slightly by pulling at it, and causing an insignificant contribution to warping the rock and dust of the moon with the strength of your own personal tide. But the scale involved is stupid, and so there's no point in talking about your effect on the moon, or your quantum presence at the store.

 Your cloud is not so easy to split in two due to your size, which is why the electron can behave in ways that you can't. You have too many electrons in you to get them to all go to the store at once, and the first electron that tries gets replaced by a new one from the movies before you notice anything happened. So when we look at you, we don't see you being omnipresent and flickering around place to place, we see you sitting at home on your computer. Every now and then, we do see electrons appear and disappear from the movies and the store though. Maybe some of them are yours.

text:
The universe is weird. 

The elections don't really orbit the nucleus. It is located everywhere it can be located, simultaneously and probabilistically...and in this probabilistic state it just surrounds the nucleus like a cloud.

The electron orbital cloud is a probabilistic representation of everywhere the electron exists 99%.

The electron has kenetic energy and momentum, but there is no motion.

When something successfully interacts with the probability cloud, and it reduces where the electron can exist, the probability cloud collapses to a smaller state...which we call a particle.

The SSD (the storage device) in your phone uses this weirdness to "teleport" electrons accross barriers...and thus stores bits of information.

That probability cloud can change size and shape. E.g. by "heating" or by employing a magnetic field.

In the SSD, a magnetic field is used to stretch the probability clouds of many electron accross a barrier. When the electron clouds collapse, some will collapse to a point on the other side of the barrier... effectively "teleporting" electrons accross a barrier.

In semiconductor chips, this can be a bad thing. Heat causes the cloud to increase in size, and electrons can thus "teleport" into unwanted places...which results in instability in its operation. The hotter the chip, the more unwanted "teleportations".

This effect also playes a role in the nuclear fusion of protons...which happens randomly... everywhere. But is infinitesimaly unlikely. Heat and higher density helps improve the odds...but is still infinitesimaly small.
Hence why the Sun creates less heat per mass than your human body. 
But another way to improve the odds of a fusion event between two protons is just to increase the sheer number of protons (the sun has that advantage, while people trying to develop fusion reactors, do not...which is why it's such a difficult goal to achieve)

text:
@RaiAuri  

Intuition involves emotion.

It seems more like you are expressing your feelings on the subject rather than any knowledge on the subject, with some random unrelated concepts and phrases that is reminiscent of mumble rap.

A field is a physical phenomenon that can be measured with an instrument or calculated, represented by a number or another tensor, that has a value for each point in space and time.

The problem with your theory is that atoms can physically be seperated into it subatomic particles. It's not a theory based on intuition (which is based on emotion). 
Subatomic particles are observations. As simple as that.

An electron can be shot individually....one at a time. If electrons did not exist, then there would be no electrons to seperate from atoms to create devices like CRT televisions, electron microscopes, and a multitude of other devices and natural phenomena.

You've probably heard of the double slit experiment. It works with all particles ever shot at it. Even large molecules like bucky-balls.

In this experiment, even electrons behave like waves until it interacts with something, at which point the probability wave collapses to a point.

The electron isn't whizzing around an atom or orbiting anything. It exists in a probabilistic state in the form of probability clouds called orbitals. Until something attempt to interact with it, then the wave function collapses to a point. An orbital is the region around the atom where the electron collapses to a point 99% of the time, when it interacts with something.

If your random speculation is correct, SSDs could not be designed. How can you successfully design something if your methodology is completely incorrect. 

A Theory (in physics) is a an accurate description of how a physical system behaves (it needs to accurately predict the behavior of a physical system in order to be a theory...otherwise it's just random speculation). 

Your "theory" is not a theory if it can't be applied. E.g., design an SSD with your "theory". 

You you are probably using an SSD right now. You can't say electrons don't exist, and then proceed to try and think up you own speculation on how electrons are transported accross barriers in SSDs.

In SSD's the electron isnt really teleported over the barrier, hence the inverted commas. The wave function collapses to a random point when the electron cloud interacts with something. The electron cloud is stretched accross the barrier (using a magnetic field) and sometimes, the wave function collapses on the other side of the barrier. (Which is effectively equivalent to teleporting electrons accross barriers). This creates a  electric potential difference (voltage) on the other side that can be stored and measured. This is how bits of information are written, stored and read in an SSD. 

And it was explicitly designed around the fact that electrons exist...and not only exist, but exist in a probabilistic state.

You're criticizing all these things (waves, particles, etc.) as if they're being offered as concrete facts. They're not. That isn't how science works.
Quantum mechanics is the most successfully tested field of science, but there is no respectable scientist who claims that they fully understand it. We have working models that demonstrate what we have been able to prove (in a scientific sense) via hypothesis and experimentation. But any scientist worth a damn is ready to adapt to changes that prove old theories wrong.
There is no "definition" for a wave, in the sense that you ask for, because its simply a representation of our understanding of how things work at a subatomic level.
All of your "counterpoints" are you simply trying to apply normal world physics to things that are too small to be affected in the same way by the laws that you are clinging to.

The thing is, if you have any experiments- that can create reproducible results- that you can provide to the science community, publish them.
If you're as enlightened as you pretend to be, and have such a higher understanding of how these things work, then please, share. If you're hypothesis is correct, you could revolutionize science.

text:
@rufusstanier8893  I may have the wrong understanding, but isn't space quantized? If the electron in principle could be anywhere within the universe, then its number of possible positions would then become a countable infinity (given that the universe is infinite), but I thought there was an outer limit where the probability fell to true zero? 

If the universe is of finite size and space is quantized, then the number of possible positions is finite; if the universe if infinite in size and space is quantized, then the number of possible positions is countably infinite; if the universe is infinite and space isn't quantized, then the number of possible positions is uncountably infinite, as you said. However, this last option makes two assumptions, one of which I thought scientists were sure was incorrect (I thought Max Planck had established the Plank length as the smallest division of space, but maybe it is just a theory?).
author: @alvekvale2431

text: @alvekvale2431  You're not wrong. Current thinking is that space must be quantized in order for quantum particles to interact via gravity, but afaik no one knows concretely how it works. The mathematics used to generate these models treats spacetime as smooth and non-quantized, and Planck scale is very, very much smaller than the scale of atoms and electron orbitals, so I would argue that we can meaningfully treat the infinity of electron positions in this situation as uncountable (to a very good approximation, at least).
author: @rufusstanier8893

text: @rufusstanier8893  Aha, I see; the question of whether the number of possible positions is an uncountable infinity or npt is unknown due to the aforementioned uncertainties, but practically,  treating the no. of positions as an uncountable infinity works due to the mathematical models used (and they work regardless of the trueness of the Planck length,  due to its extremely small size compared to the scale of electrons and their orbitals). Very interesting topic, looking forward to when I'll be using these mathematical models myself :)

text:
it's pretty and all, but this still doesn't answer Schrodinger's question about how an electron travels from one point to the next. This only displays the potential position and also a theoretical movement.

The most rational explanation of the random point movement of the electron within an atom was actually given by Wilhelm Reich, you know that guy who had his books and research burned in the late 1940's by the FDA, as well as having a restraining order put against him for his experimentation into what he described as Orgone energy. He described the process of movement as more like a jellyfish which compresses and expands, you know pretty much how all observable things work, through a rate of induction over the propelling of something, but I digress.

This gives compression and expansion gives a far better reason to why when measured Schrodinger was capable of seeing an electron here, then an electron there until he was able to give an image of the shape of an atom. Where just basic rotational models in no way give any form of explanation to how an electron has the ability to jump from one area of space to another.

But then again, when you have a following of a theory (which holds no references) which states that all things are particles, then you often "get lost following equation after equation until you no longer have any basis of reality" thanks N. Tesla for that observation. 

Still hats off to the awesome observation of the visualization of what balls moving around something are. If you really want to blow your mind, have everything moving in a 3 dimensional s curve which compresses and expands, then see what your model looks like :D, should show you the aspect that Schrodinger missed in his mapping of the atom. text: To add to the complexity, keep into account that these orbitals are only valid for the neutral hydrogen atom, and these orbitals are only "visually correct" for that atom. When we have more than one electron, we cannot represent the orbitals analytically (e.g. with an exact mathematical formula). However, we can use the hydrogen atoms orbitals as the "primary colors" to represent the more nuanced orbitals of larger atoms, more or less (with a vast approximation in the analogy) how we combine red green and blue to produce any color. The truth is not the orbitals. The truth can be described using the orbitals.

What a fantastic video! 
About the angular momentum I'd argue it's the fact that the electron's wavefunction in position space transforms in a manner that we associate in classical physics as "rotation", is the reason why we call the associated Hermitian operator (observable) angular momentum. 
Tbh, we should have done away with the idea of orbits/orbitals as soon as we found we were wrong about the orbiting, but alas, we are still drawing those misleading loops in atoms. 
TL;DR: There's no orbiting going on in the orbitals.

text:
IMHO, the whole problem in describing electron motion around an atom's nucleus is the misuse of the term "orbit" itself, which when most people hear the word "orbit" they immediately think of satellite orbits around larger massive bodies like a moon orbiting a planet or the planets orbiting the star.

I prefer to think of electron motion around an atom's nucleus as 'clouds' – or more precisely, probability clouds.  I think this more accurately portrays the life of an electron as it jumps about an atom's nucleus.  A cloud can be up close and personal or it can be lofty and remote.  It's all a matter of the energy relationship between the electron and the atom's nucleus.

text:
@AkamiChannel  : It is different because, kind of as you said, we can’t talk about the position of an electron until measurement. Quantum mechanics tell us it is accurate to say the electrons are in all of those spots at the same time and that they pick one of the eigenstates (thanks Wikipedia) once they are measured. One of the spots, to make it simple.

It’s a little like the Shrödinger’s cat experiment. Only difference being it wouldn’t work with a cat in real life, because its size is much bigger than its De Broglie wavelength, so applying quantum mechanics to such a macroscopic system would be faulty.

author: @nouche

text: @AkamiChannel  "well they kind of are smeared though until they are measured" Well, that's just the standardized confusion about the meaning of wavefunctions (WFs) I see both in the literature and the pop media all the time. LSS, the Copenhagen interpretation (the one I essentially subscribe to - with the minor addition of (some) modern decoherence findings) is an epistemic one, unlike say dBB or MW, which are ontic (a more-or-less pedagogical table is in https://arxiv.org/pdf/1509.04711.pdf ). WFs are merely tools to calculate the probability of a given outcome, they're not the thing (electrons, nuclei, etc.) itself; there is no "smearing" here, as in say when we smear butter across bread, and to claim otherwise not only adds needless conceptual complication (how the WF collapses? Why is entanglement so spooky?), but it also reveals a lack of appreciation for stochastic thinking (is a box of classical gas a "smear" of all possible microstates of said gas till we "observe" it, somehow?)

the n l and m represent the principle, angular, and magnetic quantum numbers. They're essentially coordinates on a periodic table like battleship.
n is the row number, l is what type of orbital (s=0, p=1, d=2, f=3,...) and m is the last orbital filled on a scale -2, -1 , 0, 1, 2 using a d orbital as an example.
3:05 is a weird one because there's just no way in hell H is going to have an electron configuration that of tungsten.

text:
@moegreen3870  It's a vaguely similar concept in that both use instancing, but unlike a particle system,  Blender's geometry nodes access all (or as much as is currently available) of a given object's data and let you manipulate that data in various ways. Which, for example, allows you to use distance calculations to have all the instances avoid collisions - something particle systems aren't capable of (which is why you usually need a Houdini expert for making complex particle systems - that's the OG geometry node program). In the video's case that wasn't necessary ofc, but stuff like quickly changing the cloud shape/color/size all benefitted from being part of a node system instead of a particle system.

And yeah, you can do all sorts of stuff involving deformation and manipulation that doesn't involve point distribution, although I'd say that's the most straightforward use case

text:
The way I understand atomic orbitals is that since electrons exhibit wave-like properties, electrons being near each other in the atom has their wave interact in multiple different ways. These interactions amplify themselves and suppress themselves in different spots, giving rise to the orbitals' shapes, where suppressed waves explain the areas where it's not possible to find electrons. This also explains why Hydrogen has a "solid" spherical orbital with no gaps, because there's only one electron, so no interference.

It's the same phenomenon as Chladni plates, but in 3d.

text: I would like to add that these are not the shape of atoms, but rather the shape of specific orbitals for one specific element. It represents the probability density of an electron, which depends on its quantum numbers. And since the real atomic wavefunction is a linear combination of many states, the atom is all of these orbitals at the same place at the same time. Where the electron is we don't know. What we know is in which orbital it is, and the density probability of that particular orbital. But as soon as you add another electron, or as soon as any other atom is in place, then you get a linear combination of each specific orbital and this image falls apart. This is a great visualization, but unfortunately the atom is way more complicated.

author: @ralphstern2845

text:
Hmm... I mean, it's pretty. And it does communicate something about atoms. But it leaves out a huge portion of understanding of what an atom is, what an electron is, what the orbitals and their energy levels actually mean and why they exist in discrete forms like that with gaps in between.

I'm not 100% sure how to do a better visualization but I think you could push it to the next level by first showing this... then showing a standing wave illustration in a box or the like, then showing how by being orbits, those standing waves become (roughly) circular and yet are still constrained in terms of boundary conditions, so ultimately you have another animation of an atom as sort of a "bag of wobbly-wavey wave rings".

And then you could combine them in a couple of different ways. A simple overlay could be one. Then maybe take the "bag of waves" image and fuzzify/spherificate it to incorporate some of the fuzzy ball-of-balls visual from this video. And finally take the fuzzy ball-of-balls viz and show the balls following constrained wavelengths and gradually blurring them until they become the waves of the other one?

I dunno, I just feel like a big piece of why the orbitals are shaped how they are needs an understanding of the effective boundary conditions that give rise to the discrete nature of the allowed orbitals, and this graphic really doesn't convey that at all. It also didn't seem to do much to represent the fact that each orbital doesn't have its own exclusive region of space.

So... nice progression on the path toward a better visualization of an atom, but... sadly I'm not sure this is the end of that journey. But it is a really promising idea that could definitely have a place in that final representation.

text:
​ @vaukest5888  You legit have zero idea what you're talking about.
Chromium isn't a "search engine template", it is an open source browser. A browser is nowhere near the same thing as a search engine. I have no idea why you're pulling things out of your ass.
A browser literally performs one fundamental function: it sends HTTP requests to webservers from domains (which get resolved to IP addresses by DNS), receives back the HTML hypertext from the webserver (+ the CSS styling and JS scripts), then parses that hypertext and styling to display things into the browser window in the order of the DOM and runs the JS code the webserver also provides and allows the user to interact with the elements. This is called a "website".
A search engine is just a WEBSITE. NOT A BROWSER. A browser DISPLAYS websites and a search engine IS a website.
"Search engine templates" are things like Searx, an open search engine instance someone can configure and run on a private webserver. Browsers are NOT websites. Browsers DISPLAY websites, they are NOT websites.
Yes, Google Search is the default search engine on Chromium-based browsers. All this means is that when the user types text that isn't a URL into the URL box, the browser automatically sends the Google search engine webserver a request with the user's text as the search query, and automatically routes the user there and displays the results. A search engine is a WEBSITE, connected to a WEBSERVER. NOT a browser, which is a client-side program that parses HTTP requests.
Please, stop talking because you have literally no idea what you're talking about. Dude, you're actually delusional. You're saying one thing and then saying a completely unrelated thing as if that is proof for one thing being another thing. You're the one who has no idea what Chromium is. DuckDuckGo and Ecosia are based off of Bing, and Microsoft licenses their search server to the companies to let them operate. Opera is a Chromium-based browser, DuckDuckGo and Ecosia are Bing-based search engines.
But I know you won't concede to the fact that you know literally nothing because after all, incompetent people are blissfully unaware of their own incompetence.

author: @Lone.Willow

text:
Well this is without a doubt a beautiful rendition and gives some kind of an idea what different orbital configurations might look like in 3D space (especially due to these low probability density areas). But to use it as an academical depiction of an atom it needs quite some rework. The rendition gives off two false notions: those blobs aren't electrons (even though it was mentioned in the video) and the spatial scale is out of proportion. I'd like to think of it as a cloudy grayish transparent round portion of space, which can deform and expand, based on different electron configurations taking up different metric of space. A cloudy ball? For reference I also recommend molecule isodensity images. An atom is (probably) not like this very spotty and patterned thing. These models are based on hydrogen, who has 1 electron. Literally 1. Is it really correct to depict 1 electron atoms like this? With hundred spots similar to electrons, but not really being them. It's kinda ironical to promote a better/simpler visualization of atoms and then use wave function in the video to clarify the depiction and not really showing atom as an real unit itself, but a 3D model of probability density. For most people who have not studied chemistry in at least undergrad, this is already too complex to fully grasp. And without understanding the underlying statistical idea, it just comes off as if this is what atoms look like. Very grainy blobs.

Nevertheless it's really an awesome rendition! Didn't mean any harm with my comment, just trying to fuel the conversation on this topic. Atomic orbitals deserve a lot more attention than they currently get.

text:
Question to both @minutephysics and @physicsgirl:  This 3D visual representation highlights the energy levels of Hydrogen.  My understanding of the electron cloud probability orbitals for Hydrogen is pretty solid.  This visualization reinforces that further.  Where I have difficulty (and stumped two chemistry professors) is understanding what happens with electrons beyond the s orbital?  

Example: Carbon C(1s2,2s2,2p2) When energy level increases to shift to a higher electron shell does one electron shift, some electrons or all?  I envisioned the lowest level of energy required would be shifting the outer most electron into the next up position so C(1s2,2s2,2p2) would become C(1s2,2s2,2p1&3) or maybe C(1s2,2s2,2p1,3s1).  What would your knowledge of physics and chemistry suggest?  I understand all this hangs under the caveat of probability but this model seems to illustrate that very fact.  

Finally, thank you both for providing great insights in physics and science in general.  And thank you in advance if you tackle this question.

text:
The title was a little underwhelming for the main content you shared in the video, but I stuck till the end bc I know the quality of what you create.
Personally, as a physics student, I grew more comfortable with the idea of non-local wave-described electron (and atomic entities in general) so I find it intuitive (or at least comfortable and not so fuzzy to imagine) by now to speak of a probability distribution of electron location on measurement, so I was not expecting much to be added to my visual or intellectual conception conception of the phenomena.
Yet, the idea of solving  equations governing fluid mechanics with the potential distribution of atomic system is very intriguing and - for some reason - very neat.

I really liked watching the resulting animations but the question on my mind was while I was watching them and being fascinated by them: "what water would look like if it were subject to the inverse radial potential?" and another question was "how can such a potential be physically created?"
These were very intriguing questions you stirred by your nice work.

So thank you for your beautiful insights.

text:
See, the thing with electron diagrams is that they're not intended to portray how electrons in atoms actually are, and that's entirely necessary because when not being interacted with, electrons don't really "orbit" the nucleus at all, and they don't really have a definite location at any point in time.

The wavefunction diagrams don't show where electrons likely are, they show where the electrons are likely to be when they are interacted with. Thus, even they don't provide an accurate representation of the structure of an atom.

text: These do look extremely lovely and thank you for the great video.   I would very much enjoy seeing what the transition between orbitals looks like with these simulations!  That said, one doesn't really need to do Bohmian dynamics to get a feel for orbital dynamics in quantum mechanics.  As implied in the very end, if one generated "smoke-rendered" cloudy Schrödinger wave functions as density visualizations, but kept the phase information and ran it dynamically, keeping track of the real and imaginary parts as colors, you'd get the same basic pictures.  Another advantage to the Schrödinger approach is that it is a linear PDE that can be solved at the sophomore level in analytical form for hydrogen.  The de Broglie–Bohm approach, while incorporating the Schrödinger equation, is non-linear and not so accessible in closed form.  Finally, with the de Broglie–Bohm approach one is left with the tension of why the apparently literally orbiting "non-electron electron particles" in the simulation aren't radiating and may create more confusion -- this mystery was one driving motivation for early quantum theory and the Schrödinger equation in the first place.

ARTHUR CAYLEY

"Oh WRETCHED race of men, to space confined!

What honour can ye pay to him, whose mind

To that which lies beyond hath penetrated?

The symbols he hath formed shall sound his praise,

And lead him on through unimagined ways

To conquests new, in worlds not yet created.

First, ye Determinants! In ordered row

And massive column ranged, before him go,

To form a phalanx for his safe protection.

Ye powers of the nth roots of - 1!
Around his head in ceaseless* cycles run,

In n dimensions flourished unrestricted."

to clarify, this representation is a point-by-point location probability (chance) of a stationary atom.

the problems with atoms and quantum understanding is we in the physical world (reality) cannot observe/measure both the location of an atom or the energy, we are ultimately incapable of knowing both properties of them.

if we could see an atom for real with immense detail, all of these dots would not be there. as best as we can tell, there would only be a number (N) of corrosponding electrons in "orbit" and in reality, if it was at all possible, we would see their positions individually. however, "the uncertainty principle" dictates we can't see it as giant creatures by comparison to these insanely tiny objects.

if you've ever seen a macroscopic photo of a strand of hair, then you already understand the details we are incapable of seeing with just our eyes without technological help. go smaller than that and see headlice in great detail, or waterbears, these things only serve to exacerbate our inability to see the world in all the details it has to offer. now concieve the idea that each of these things are made up of trillions (1,000,000,000,000) of atoms and begin to understand the complex nature of such tiny objects. they move fast. real fast.

i'm shyte with science and math, but i think Hydrogen has but 1 electron, and the video is demonstrating Hydrogen, and all the points you see are places in which the electron might be found. once you find it, you will not know which way it's moving (spinning... whatever) and if you found which way it was spinning, you would never know where it is in that moment. so the diagram/animation serves to show us what an atom of hydrogen might look like if we could even look at it.

this goes for every atom. if you thought Hydrogen confused you, with one electron, you'd probably split your brain looking at something with 40 electrons.

by the way, the rainbowed representations, i think, are atoms with a high number of electrons, giving a visual representation of possible positions the electrons could be.

text:
Be careful, that's at best a bad summary and at worst just incorrect. The model of an atom looking like our solar system with small ball going in a circle around big ball very very quickly became outdated as we figured out the orbitals represented in the video.
But the basic reason why planets and electrons don't just fly away is the same: they are attracted to the center. Electrons are negatively charged, nuclei positively. So they attract eachother. The electron fell into the potential well of the nucleus, radiated its energy away and like a ball sitting in a hole or the earth going around the sun, it's stuck there now. To get it back out you have to give it some energy and then it'll leave. That's exactly what we see in the photoelectric effect for example

text:
@sciencegremlin8307  "Like the cherry around the pit?" 
Sure, you can think of it like that. It's not incredibly accurate obviously, but maybe a decent mental picture as long as you don't take it too seriously. One note: The proportion of electron orbital to nucleus is massive; if the cherry pit is your nucleus, the orbitals are more the size of a football stadium. 

"By what physical process?"
Ropes and elastic bands are big objects made out of trillions of atoms while we are talking about the inside of a single one, so those can't be it. They're held together by the electromagnetic force. You've seen it before, like when you rub a balloon on your hair and make it stand up or when two magnets attract eachother. There doesn't have to be any matter connecting them, the electromagnetic field is its own thing. Similarily the earth is not connected to the sun via some big stick or something, the force of gravity holds them together.

Now let me address the energy part first: Energy is a number we assign to a system, just like mass or charge. The very basics you should know: there are different forms (like kinetic energy, potential energy, heat energy, etc.) which can be turned into eachother but the total amount always stays the same. Energy also is what allows you to do work. An example: Let's say you want to pick up a rock. Your muscles turn chemical energy from the food you ate into heat energy and kinetic energy. Picking up the rock, that kinetic energy gets converted to potential energy and if you let go, it turns back into kinetic as the rock falls.
So energy is a property of something. When the electron gives off energy, something has to carry it and that usually is a particle called a photon. If it's just the right amount of energy, we see this as light.

Now let's connect energy and attraction: If you have two magnets you'll notice that they want to stick together (in a certain configuration). This is because close to each other, they have less energy than when far apart. So when the magnet is close to the other, it has only little of a certain type of energy and as you get farther away, this energy gets higher and higher. If you would graph this, representing the energy with some height, you might say that it looks like a valley or a well. We call this the potential or potential well and the energy potential energy. Notice: the well isn't some physical structure made of matter or something like that; it just refers to how the potential energy develops with increasing distance from the target. You could say that the potential is caused by the attractive force or the other way around, doesn't really matter for us. 
But a real well is also an example of a potential well, created by the force of gravity. The earth also sits in the gravitational potential of the sun.

It's been quite a while since I've seen someone so eager to ask questions and I love it. If you have more questions - and I'm sure you do- please don't hesitate to ask. However, there is only so much I can do for you through youtube comments. I really think you'd enjoy some elementary physics education; there are lots of great, free resources online.

text:
How would you visualize standing waves on a drumhead? Or sound waves in a closed room? It's exactly the same principle. Those lobes and donuts in atomic diagrams are just regions of maximum amplitude in electron wavefunctions.

Don't worry about where the electrons "are". They're everywhere, because electrons are waves, not particles---at least when they're not being observed. They seem like particles when particle detectors detect them, but that doesn't mean they're particles when they're undisturbed. You can think of particle detectors as wave-squishing machines that temporarily force wave energy into a tiny volume. There are no point particles in quiescent atoms, only standing waves that are trapped in the electrostatic potential well created by the protons in the nucleus.

You are misunderstanding. The electron doesn't drop some physical distance within its orbital, its state changes from one orbital to another, lower one. These are discrete steps of energy.

author: @lunkel8108

text:
@lunkel8108  .. Dropping from one orbit to a lower orbit creates an energy wave. That wave is specific to the material/molecule/atom itself....and in some instances, those waves are within the spectrum of light.  For example, when you excite noble gases, they give off a specific wavelength of light with an EXACT measurement, every time, every...time....always....all the time...the same.

This means the distance between the orbits are exactly the same, as the wave produced is exactly the same. To conclude in any other way on how physics works is to deny your eyes or the instruments themselves. Unless you think that atoms are somehow alive?  That you are stating that an electron has coherent thought to create a wave based on what it is orbiting, and despite where it is in a cloud of possibility, it knows to always give up the exact same energy when dropping down into another cloud of possibility.

But sure, you all have gone to college, and you all know exactly how atoms work, despite the fact that we have no instruments able to see at that precision......that we only know the outcomes of reflective properties and the measurements it produces, so we postulate on a LOT of things.  The models work because it explains the error from the data....but then you look at something like wavelengths of excitation and getting exact numbers, which kills the whole idea that error even exists.

Maybe, just maybe, physics and scientists are missing a crucial piece of evidence? Couldn't be some Joe Shmoe in the youtube comments pointing out garbage through some tomfoolery joking at the expense of people who are supposed to be geniuses, to really make people think about the bullshit you are being fed....nope, not at all.

I'll give you a hint....scientists are just humans who were given pieces of paper proving that they learned from other humans on stuff they thought was correct. Models change and get more precise....clouds are just the imprecision we currently face in science.
author: @sabriath

text:
@sabriath  You're still fundamentally misunderstanding this. The atomic orbitals are energy eigenstates. So of course going from one to the other is going to emit the same amount of energy each time, there is no probability involved with the energy of the electron. You seem to think that a superposition in position implies a superposition in energy and an energy eigenstate must be a position eigenstate but that is just very simply incorrect. You're thinking way too classically. 
Look, if you want to critique a model for having logical contradictions, that's great. However to do that effectively, you have to understand it. What you are doing is finding inconsistencies in your flawed understanding of the model, not the actual model itself. Go ahead and study some introductory quantum mechanics, you will see that what you wrote makes no sense and this isn't a problem. There are plenty of great, free resources online such as the MIT OpenCourseWare program.
author: @lunkel8108

text:
@lunkel8108  No, what I am implying is similar to a set of stairs. The energy required to move from step one to step two is the same because the distance is the same....therefore if we were to "excite" something up that 1 step, when it falls back down, the distance it travels creates an energy wave.  That wave is determined by the energy, therefore the wavelength is connected to the position it fell.  Because energy cannot be created nor destroyed, it must be conserved....therefore when it falls, the wave tells us the energy and therefore the distance of the fall.

Well, if an electron is in a cloud of possibilities, and it falls to another cloud of possibilities, then the energy it produces has a minimum and maximum range (determined by the distance from the highest point of the higher cloud to the lowest point of the lower cloud as the maximum distance it can fall and the distance from the lowest point of the higher cloud to the highest point of the lower cloud as the minimum distance). This creates a spectrum of energy that can be emitted by the release of an excited state by falling 1 position and still be viable within the cloud model.  This would suggest that exciting noble gases would result in a spectrum of wavelengths within that minmax range.  We do not detect this, so the cloud model is not correct.

You can say all the mumbojumbo you want that you've gotten from textbooks and your teachers, or even your science friends....but you are all humans, and you are just repeating the gibberish you've heard without using your own brain to realize that humans make mistakes.  They can't even agree on the double-slit experiment on how observation works.....when the instrument itself is the culprit, but whatever.

You humans will figure it out in about 67 years from now. Fun times.
author: @sabriath

text:
@sabriath  No, again, you are just fundamentally misunderstanding this. You try to work with single particles when that is very much not appropriate and doesn't work. You have to work with the wavefunction itself. There is no single electron that falls from one specific position with a specific energy to another specific position with another specific energy. At all points in an orbital does the electron have the same energy. The wave function goes from one energy eigenstate to another.
You know when flat earthers say something like "gravity can't exist because then all the water would fall off the earth" because they fundamentally misunderstand what the model of gravity actually says? You are doing something very similar. You say "this theory predicts that x should happen but it doesn't, so it's wrong" when the theory simply does not predict x. 

So in conclusion you have created your own confused and nonsensical model and concluded that it makes no sense. I agree with that assessment. You have already decided what physicists are saying and disproven the strawman of them in your head, so you refuse to check what the model actually is. If you want to learn what the actual model is so that you may critique it and not whatever knock-off lives in your head, you are more than welcome to do so. Like I said, I really liked the quantum mechanics courses from MIT, avaible online for free.

If you want to remain at the height of ignorance and arrogance going "I already decided that everything you say like "functions" and "vectors" is meaningless mumbojumbo you don't understand because I don't understand it", I don't mind really. Anybody with a fundamental education in chemistry or quantum mechanics will immediatly see why you are wrong and it's not like you're in some important positon where your ignorance could harm people. But for your own sake, at least consider learning a bit instead of ridiculing your own misunderstandings.

text:
Oh yeah, those'll be easy to draw on a chalkboard. Look, think of one of those "cartoony" drawings of an atom as a "schematic." You don't like the schematic, that's fine, but don't disparage the thing. There's a reason engineers use both schematics and pictorial references, and a very good reason the schematics are the ones everyone uses for reference purposes. It's clear and explanatory and if you know how to read them, you can tell by looking at the device or circuit what goes where and what it does, even if you don't know the layout or even all the specific components. When I look at the 'schematic' for an atom, I know where all the parts are, what they do, and can look up further details for a given atom, assuming I haven't memorized them. Simpler versions are basically training wheels for everyone else.

What you want is a pictorial, which isn't really literally possible because the electrons refuse to stay still. So now you have a nice CG one to reference for your viewing pleasure. Unlike circuit pictorials it's probably not very useful - or maybe it is to someone. Not very practical though, since you can't print it out on a sheet of paper for handy reference.

author: @chappyhappy8483

text:
@chappyhappy8483  The n,l,m are the quantum numbers that characterize the orbital. Roughly they mean the following: l tells you the type of orbital that it is (ball [s] vs dumbbell [p] vs double dumbbell [d], etc.). m tells you which way these are oriented. And n tells you the size/energy of the orbital. So for example a 1s orbital is a small ball and a 2s orbital is a larger, higher energy ball. (All this is very oversimplified)
In reality all of the electrons in an atom like carbon interact with each other in really complex ways that make it literally impossible to calculate an exact orbital. We can approximate but many times the basic single electron orbitals stacked on top of eachother are a good approximation. There is one big effect that changes with the element: The bigger nucleus will be more strongly charged, so it attracts the electrons more and the orbitals are basically "shrunk down" and lower energy with respect to hydrogen. This effect can be lessened by other electrons in the way and different kinds of orbitals to a better or worse job at this. This explains many of the trends in the periodic table.

For example, in a period (left to right) the elements actually get smaller as their nuclei get bigger. Oxygen is smaller than carbon for example. This is because of the extra contraction of the orbitals.
And while electronegativity usually drops within a group (top to bottom), it does so less/ even can increase from the 3rd period to the 4th period because that's where you get d orbitals and they are really bad at shielding the extra charge of the nucleus.

text:
"A WORSE Way To Picture Atoms" there fixed your tittle. 

Someone who does not understand the contemporary illustrations of atomic orbitals (i.e. the fuzzy clouds), will not only be superbly confused by your representation of atomic orbitals, but will most likely misunderstand completely how atoms may look like. 

The rule is simple... BE SIMPLE. Your illustration is nothing else than a much more complex version of the 'fuzzy clouds' orbital representation and a worse one as well. You say that every dot represents where an electron might be. But what about all the spaces between the dots? Are those spots areas in which an electron can not be at any given moment in time and space? Do these spots change? Are all of those dots equally likely to represent the location of an electron? Etc...Etc...Etc...

Your attempt fails to address the exact same issue you are trying to solve.

The qm equations give a sort of the complexed root of the likelihood density.

This cannot work.

I mean, 90+% of the people mess up classical mechanics in the moment they are confronted with classical rotation. To them, vector products are pure magic.

Or electro-magnetism (Maxwell)?

C'ommon, Henry! You are messing up the people's minds completely by providing catchy but absolutely misleading eye candy.

@ObjectsInMotion  If I may; I've honestly never seen anyone with your stance on this before, it's genuinely incredibly interesting.

The answer is: it depends. 
The majority can be wrong about objective facts, because nothing about the majority says that they have to be well informed. 
Just because the majority back in medieval Europe thought that bloodletting was an effective cure to disease, doesn't mean that they were right. And if two out of three people in a room believes that the earth is flat, that doesn't mean that it is.
Claiming such a thing would obviously be ridiculous. And you haven't claimed such a thing, as far as I know.

When it comes to opinion and morality however, the common consensus (since you place great value on it) is that it's up to individuals. Everyone has different senses of morality, and while a good moral compass is backed up by arguments and deeper philosophy, there is (at least as of yet) no right answer to most moral questions. Though, some moral viewpoints are far stronger than others, just as it is with all of philosophy.

Once again I feel you're merging morality with laws. They're not the same. 
In an ideal world they would be, but here on earth right now they most certainly are not. 
(Does that mean that every law in every country is morally just, for instance? Does it mean that mob justice against a minority of people is justified?)

And then there's the fact that democracy doesn't actually allow people to choose laws. Direct democracy basically doesn't exist on a national level. Though I assume you are aware of this, obviously.

Edit: I know this is getting quite long, but I need to correct something I missed. Arguments from the people do indeed include everything from tastes to morals to everything else. What you are saying is almost a textbook example, from what I can tell.

text:
While I like the video and love the models, I do have the problem with the premise of "a better way to picture atoms", because that lies entirely in what their intended use is. Yes, if one wants to picture what it actually looks like (as you do), it is better, but this is rarely the case. 
More accurate isn't necessarily better. By the very nature of a model, it is a simplification of what it is portraying. A good model needs to find the balance between being accurate and being simply/easy to use. A globe is more accurate than a map, because it is in 3D, but that very same aspect often makes maps easier to use and therefore they become preferred models, because the inaccuracies doesn't matter or affect us, when we use them for their intended purpose.

Imagine if you made a video saying that a globe is a better way to picture earth, while technically true, people would probably say that you missed the point about maps. Especially if you gave a Minutephysics approved version of a map. The usefulness of this map would lie entirely in its projection and its intended use, so to say that this is a better version, is at best misleading and somewhat arrogant. You are comparing models that have different purposes and approve of yours as it fits your purpose, but that is hardly a fair assessment.

text:
Meh, though beautiful, as a researcher in science education I am not too fond of that representation, but that would be actually a long story.
Let's take at least one example: You say that one dot, together with its trajectory represents where the electron might be  and what velocity it has. But that is not correct. A dot represents where you might find an electron, if you care to measure its position, before measurement there is no electron with a specific position. And if you measure the position of the electron and it is at that one position, the velocity would be so gigantic, that it would just leave the nucleus.
So again, the representations are really really beautiful, but I fear the do not help with any misconceptions about atoms. Sorry.

however the other day i came across a "web3" app that interfaced in realtime with a crypto blockchain which was rendering interactive 2d physics (a cartoony representation of the blockchain) to a web canvas extremely rapidly... it looked like around 100+ objects rendering at easily over 120+ fps on a GTX 1080

i was surprised and taken aback because i am so accustomed to that ancient slow web rendering from 2005 lmao

the author said he built his app with "Unity WebGL" tech or something like that?  (i think i got the exact name wrong but for sure he mentioned "Unity", that i remember 100% for sure)

the Unity engine is very popular in videogames and the company is gigantic with over 3,000 employees!


with such a gigantic workforce my spidey sense tells me they have finetuned web rendering and made it l33t, so i believe you will find very good results if you investigate Unity Technologies... the company "id Software" has achieved mind melting graphics with an employee base of 200 to 300 or so building their own inhouse engine, so i can only dream or guess what is possible with over 3000 employees... my guess is that Unity has a whole team dedicated to web rendering


but i don't know this 100% for sure since the app i viewed was 2D sprites and technically not 3D shaded objects... still, the great performance i witnessed gives me the sense that their 3D version is probably blazing fast too


i'm currently extremely overwhelmed with work, but if free time allows i may be able to dig deeper into this subject

text:
Science Revolution  - "How a tiny particle comprises waves of electromagnetic radiation?"

in my personal opinion the term "travelling wave pulse" is a better term than "moving particle"

a way to visualize a wave pulse in a sort of simplified 2D way is these pictures:
https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/b/b0/Wave_packet_%28dispersion%29.gif

https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/2/25/Wave-train-superposition-all.svg

https://i.ytimg.com/vi/LyVo_mJvkpQ/hqdefault.jpg


the .gif is very nice because it is animated! 

now that 2D visualization doesn't encompass the 3D traits, so it is just a stepping stone to greater concepts, and should not be considered the final visualization


imo one of the nice things about that gif is the wave pulse has width or spatial extent, which is one of the traits of a particle (if the particle is not a "point particle")

the third image also kinda shows this... what is labelled the "envelope"... in a way could be considered like a 2D cross section of a particle maybe? :p

in the sense that it occupies a finite portion of space... it has "spatial extent"



although this is just a simplified 2D image... i think in 3D it gets more complicated and might even involve a sort of "spinning corkscrew motion" that i don't really understand :p


i am a physics amateur and do not really understand it

these images and videos i am sharing should only be considered as "blobby vague ideas that do not fully explain anything but only hint at possible tiny tiny subsectors of the subject", "suggestions", "conceptual explorations", and absolutely should not be considered as anything at all like a "final word" on anything!   because i do not understand it as a whole at all :)
author: @moegreen3870

text:
Science Revolution  - "What is photon made of?  How photons move in space, air, water and glass?"

if i remember correctly, James Maxwell from the 1800s thought that they were wave pulses in a medium that he called "the Aether" or sometimes he called it "the luminiferous Aether"... so as for what photons are made of, i think in some ways they can be thought of as "made of Aether"... like travelling wave disturbances in the Aether maybe?    in a similar sense water waves are "made of water" perhaps?

and if you are wondering well then what is the Aether made of?  as far as i am aware, so far nobody knows!  :p
(but there are many interesting guesses about what it might be made of)

now keep in mind, i think many do not even believe the Aether exists in the first place hehe... in fact i think there are many thousands who believe the Aether idea to be "stankin hogwash" lmao... possibly in part due to the wide influence of Einstein?  i'm not sure


some 40 years after Maxwell, Einstein tried to convince his peers that the Aether was a "mathematically superfluous" concept and should be forgotten about because he felt it did not contribute much to final understanding or something like that?   i think he saw it as an unnecessary complication of sorts?

Einstein had enormous respect for Maxwell, but i think he might have made the effort to toss the theoretical concept out because he wanted to simplify calculations for his peers... at least thats what i suspect was the motivation

however I have heard rumours that in later years Einstein regretted this effort of his to toss out the Aether :)

Paul Dirac spent many years trying to revive the Aether concept... spread out across the span 1936 to 1980 i think Dirac spent more than five years, possibly even more than ten years, on this effort... which in my opinion is very significant from a formidable man like him!


as for why photons could move in space, air, water, and also glass:
Maxwell believed that the Aether was all pervading filling every possible location of the Universe... that there was no such thing as a section of the Universe where Aether was not present



now keep in mind that all of these concepts are "educated guesses"... all of science is a gigantic reverse engineering process of mind blowing proportions, spanning many centuries and thousands of people :)

as these people proceed to reverse more and more of the Universe's splendid hidden engineering, at the vanguard of the effort they are equipped mainly with something akin to "new guesses" or perhaps "hypothesis" is a better word


so Maxwell doesn't know these things for sure, they are just his best guess... but in my opinion it is a very good guess :)


anyway, if the Aether is all-pervading, then it might follow that photon pulses can travel inside of glass because glass would be "99% Aether, 1% glass atoms"... where normally the phrase is "99% Empty Space, 1% glass atoms"... in my opinion it is useful to replace the phrase "Empty Space" with the word "Aether" :p



if you are wondering, where did these figures of 99% and 1% come from?

i think it might have been the man from down unda, Ernest Rutherford, along with his assistant somewhere around the year 1910 or thereabouts who performed hundreds perhaps thousands of hours of experiments to try to figure out how much space does the nucleus of atoms occupy... and if i remember right he found that the spatial extent of the nucleus is very very small... that the majority of the atom is "empty space"... and i think Rutherford's peers in later years determined that electrons are likewise extremely tiny...

in fact i think some people model the electron as a point particle with zero spatial extent!   (me personally i think the idea of zero extent is nonsense and crazy, but keep in mind that i am a physics newb so i dunno for sure what i am talking about lmao... but yeah zero spatial extent to me sounds nutty and dopey :p)

text:
Science Revolution  - "How photon becomes EM wave?"

well, as far as i have heard a photon is already considered an EM wave kinda sorta, i think?   not 100% sure :p


if you are wondering how are photons created, i think there might be at least four ways that photons can be emitted from other particles due to motion, and there are a bunch of other ways it can happen through decay processes

(and concerning those decay processes, i personally believe photon emission is due to sorta hidden internal accelerated motions during the "explosion" or "decay" of the original source particle...if this unverified personal belief is ultimately objectively true, then possibly all photons in the universe can trace their origin back to an acceleration event where a charge density was given a sudden impulse shove or a sudden impulse pull?   i'm not sure, but it is what i suspect... i mentioned "pulls" because acceleration can be a negative number, so deceleration would be included too... but possibly there are alternative photon origins that i am not aware of :p)

the four motion-related ways i have heard of: synchrotronically accelerated radiation, linearly accelerated radiation, dropping to a lower energy level in an atomic orbital shell, and hmmm shoot i forget what the 4th way was!!  :p


if a charged particle like an electron or a positron is accelerated in a "curved way", it will emit a photon... this is called "synchrotron radiation" and was first closely observed by four scientists in New York in 1947

if an electron is following a circular "racetrack-like" path i think this means acceleration is taking place constantly, because its vector of travel is changing constantly, which means acceleration must be taking place... acceleration/deceleration is the only way an inertial vector can change i think...

so i think this means during this time of following such a path it is emitting perhaps thousands or even millions of photons?   i'm not sure on the number of photons that fly out lol :)

but if the direction/inertial vector is constantly changing many thousands of times per second, i think this translates to many thousands of photons per second?



linear acceleration of a charged particle in a straight line also seems like it emits a photon at each impulse of acceleration... i'm not sure when it was discovered... possibly by Heinrich Hertz in the 1880s?     i think Hertz radiowave experimental setup pushed electrons down linear paths... which emitted radiowaves... which are considered photons... but whether Hertz knew what was taking place is another question hehe...

i think possibly he was mostly mystified and dazzled by the phenomena, because he was one of the early radiowave pioneers with not many shoulders to lean or stand on... he didn't have many he could ask for tips or advice... he had to figure out alot of the subject by himself... so possibly linear acceleration was recognized by a different later scientist who came after Hertz?   i dunno i am not sure :p


if an electron drops to a lower energy level while in the orbital shells of an atomic nucleus, this is another way that photon emission can take place... i believe experiments have repeatedly proven that the energy of the emitted photon matches the drop in energy 100% exactly, like perfect match down to the exact expected electron-volt amount to many decimal places!   i think this was discovered in the 1910s or 1920s?

cannot remember who discovered it... possibly a scientist named Balmer?  but possibly somebody else... wished i could remember :p


and then in addition to these "acceleration-originated" ways of photon creation, there are many ways that particles can decay into multiple other particles which sometimes includes a photon or two... (although like i said above, i kinda suspect these ways are ultimately also acceleration-originated as well, but just in a kind of hidden or obscured way, because a decay process is probably a chaotic mess similar to an explosion... so it is harder to say what is going on for sure in a nice orderly way, because so many things are happening close to the same time, and also some particle decays happen incredibly fast!)

like if i remember right, sometimes the Higgs Boson can decay into two photons and some other stuff?  (the kitchen sink comes flying out LOL)

can't remember for sure but something like that!  :)

text: @ick-625  Actually, you can always have full knowledge over a particle's position and momentum simultaneously. It's just that both of them are functions (for position, it's a function of x, for momentum, it's a function of p), where one is the Fourier transform of another. Neither are single points, because if it was a single point, then it'd be the Dirac delta function. And the Fourier transform of the Dirac delta function is a sinusoidal that extends to infinite magnitude, which is very unphysical, so you can't have that. The uncertainty principle is about the standard deviations of those functions, when viewed as distributions.

text: Even if Heisenberg's uncertainty principle is often called "uncertainty principle", it's not actually an uncertainty, but rather an indetermination. An uncertainty means that it's our fault that we can't calculate two or more of the all physical magnitudes of a less-than-0,7-nanometers-sized physical entity, which is not true. The quantum behaviour is natural, not a misinterpretation of human beings. Modern phones, optic fiber, etc., work with quantum mechanics, some technological devices suddenly stop working because of quantum mechanics, some animals use quantum mechanics to orientate... Some names can be misleading, so when you read them, you need to be sure that you understand what they really mean. Like I said before, uncertainty principle is not an uncertainty but an indetermination; Big Bang is not an explosion but an expansion of space; universe expansion is not universe expansion but the expansion of space named before; etc.
