text:
Science Revolution  First, an atom is made of electrons, protons, neutrons, and quantum vacuum, and protons and neutrons are just a superposition of three quark fields, plus some gluon fields, plus more quantum vacuum. Neutrons and gluons are neutral and from quantum vacuum are made a lot of virtual particles, also called stationary waves, some of them neutral, some other of them not. 

Second, electrons are not orbiting the nucleus. We're not in Rutherford's, or in Bohr-Sommerfeld's, or in another-atomic-model-in-which-electrons-are-orbiting-the-nucleus' atomic model. We're in Quantum Field Theory's atomic model. This model is obviously quantum, and because it's quantum we need to talk about probabilities. An electron could be in an atom's nucleus and that would be an electron capture, a type of nuclear disintegration, but the probability for happening this is too low. Being not in the nucleus is more probable and being in an electron orbital is too probable.

Third, particles are not little balls, they are quantum waves, energetic excitements of their respective quantum fields.

Fourth, gravity is stronger than electric force when we talk about massive bodies, like our Earth. And, at that macroscopic level, is not gravity a force but a curvature of space produced by the stress-energy tensor of all known matter. But at quantum levels, gravity is a force, which we don't understand actually, but it's the electric force the force which wins. It's, as you say, 10^(39) times stronger than gravity at that level, but it doesn't mean that my third clarification is wrong. You don't know the value of gravity at a quantum level.

Fifth, no matter is incompressible. It might be hard to compress, depending of which matter are we talking about, but not impossible.

And sixth, as I said in my first clarification, atoms are made of electrons, protons, neutrons, and quantum vacuum, and protons and neutrons are just a superposition of three quantum fields, plus some gluon fields, plus more quantum vacuum. So atoms are not 99,999...% empty. That's just a misconception, a mix of classical and quantum's statements.
author: @diegocabrales

text:
Science Revolution  Please, be respectful.

A quantum is the minimum amount of any physical entity involved in an interaction. A quantum behaviour is the behaviour of matter whose size (diameter) is equal or less than 0.7 nm, the size of a fullerene molecule. This behaviour is not like the macroscopic one. You can have a quantum entity in a lot of positions, velocities, momentums, etc., at the same time, for example. 

A quantum wave is a synonym of quantum particle, because they are described by wavefunctions given by Quantum Field Theory, which is based on the Dirac-Jordan atomic model, the atomic model based on special relativity, written by Albert Einstein and published by him in 1905, and quantum mechanics, the branch of physics that describes the quantum behaviour of matter. All atomic models must have special relativity and quantum mechanics in consideration.

Quantum vacuum is a kind of space region that is wherever you see from which virtual particles arise. Particles are called virtual because they behave distinctly as how normal particles, also called real particles, behave. They are always stationary waves and some of them transmit the four fundamental forces, for example, although we don't know it the gravity carrier's particle, the graviton, exists or not. But we do know that the weak force carrier's particle, the W^± and Z^0 bosons, the electromagnetic force carrier's particle, the photon, and the strong force carrier's particle, the gluon and the neutral pion, exist. And we understand all that forces, but gravity, as I said before, not actually because it must be quantum mechanical at quantum levels, but if you introduce quantum mechanics in general relativity, the best tested theory of gravity written by Albert Einstein and published in 1915, appear infinities that can't be eliminated, or in other words, there is no renormalization. We need more information to write a quantum theory of gravity. And strong nuclear force carried by gluons, distinct from the one carried by neutral pions, it's not fully understood because, among other things, we do not know how it can give to hadrons, physical entities that are, among other things, the superposition of quark and gluon fields, the most of its masses if gluons are massless. And they must be massless, as science says to us.

Well, Pilot Wave Theory is deterministic, and Multiple Universe Theory is an impossible cop-out of the discussion that would have an infinite number of results for every single interaction at each infinitely small moment for every quanta in the entire universe, continuously.  So it's still magical thinking and not really deterministic.  But both predict the same results as the Copenhagen Consensus interpretation of quantum mechanics.

Science Revolution  "No known mechanism"  You mean unknown to you!  Atomic orbitals are due to quantum effects at that scale -- they very much do explain the properties of the atom.  Solid is compressible as can be demonstrated using a micrometer in parallel with a sample in a press.  Fluids are obviously compressible and you can buy bottles of pressurized gas.
Don't confuse your lack of knowledge/understanding of the theory with a lacking of the theory itself.  You're assuming you understand it completely and perfectly and it doesn't make sense; actually it doesn't make sense because you don't understand it completely.

text: Not really, the de Broglie-Bohm theory, like the video explains, allows one to visualize quantum motion as a particle guided by a "pilot wave" of probability. Though it's still not possible to pinpoint any single electron and how fast it's going you can model the "wave" it's traveling on. The same way you can't know just by watching the wave when the surfer riding it will reach the shore you can make a pretty good guess, modeling the wave allows to track the position and motion of a particle simultaneously as a probabilistic projection rather than an exact pinpoint.

text: It's possible nowadays to do "Ab-initio molecular dynamics" for small molecules at reasonable computational cost. What this involves is solving the electronic schrodinger equation over and over for consecutive snapshots of nuclear motion. Electrons are ~1000 times lighter than nuclei, so you can approximate the orbitals as changing smoothly and continuously as the nuclear trajectory progresses. This way you can effectively visualise orbitals forming bonding arrangements as nuclei approach (or breaking the bond as they move apart).

Yep, that was the only problem I had with this otherwise excellent depiction of the wave functions. He does clarify that the dots aren't actually "an" electron but still might lead people to believe that there is such a thing (what would it be "made" of?). My understanding is that the energy distribution described by the wave function is the electron, and as you say, you "particlise" it with your observation of it's interaction with whatever you're measuring it with ... Well, with the wave function at the point it interacts with whatever you're measuring it with, lol, so there is no particle interaction just discrete energy transfer letting you learn one of its properties.

text: There are a lot of problems. What an atom is, esp. a Z>1 atom, is not ^^^this^^^. An atom isn't even what quantum mechanics says it is. QM is an approximation in which the electron is a particle, so you can't get past that anyway. There are no measurements of electron positions in an atom, nor collapse to a point. All that will mislead noobs. Nevertheless, it's a pretty demonstration of both the radial and angular parts of the wave function, and it appears to include the probability current, which is novel. I have seen it with complex time evolution, but that is different from (and lesser than) probability current.
author: @DrDeuteron

text:
@gshingles   "Taint" is too harsh, I admit. But nicely animated stuff distract me from the messy business called searching for "better truth".
History taught us that even our greatest minds fell over their own feet when being blindfolded by the beauty of their own discoveries (famously, Einstein's rejection of qm comes into mind).

I lack the mathematical capabilities to understand the stuff by myself (i.e..do the math, or even understand the math).
And I don't even know, whether my wild guessing of Planck time was not utterly stupid.
AFAIK, our possible understanding of physics must end at Planck time and -length. I don't have any infomation, if the wave functions collapses in Planck time or in fact instantaneously when measuring. It's bogus anyway, since at Planck time, causality itself disappears, afaik (ouch). And the "collapse" itself, again it a model with it's own problems (->DoS has more on this).

But I try to follow Wittgenstein's advise: "Worüber man nicht sprechen kann, darüber muss man schweigen"

text:
Still that's not a correct depiction of an atom. It doesn't answer the most fundamental question which is this

"If you had an atom and you blew it up to the size of a bowling ball, what would it look like?"

The reason why you wouldn't be able to see atoms under any microscope that works with visible light, is because the wavelength of visible light is so much bigger than the atom itself. But if we were to blow up the atom to be the size of say... a bowling ball. Then that excuse doesn't apply anymore... Now the wavelength of visible light is smaller than the object we are observing (in this case the atom) and the atom is big enough so that we don't have to use microscopes... So what would it look like!?

The way I understand it. The atom will look like nothing. It will be completely invisible, just like the air... You know the air is there but you can't see it... Picture is like a spherical force field that you could probably touch (?) (although I don't really know what would happen to your hand if you do so...) and feel like something's there but you are unable to see it...

Other people suggest that it might emit light or radiation in general that you could see...

I wonder if it could have a surface and what would that feel and look like? Maybe it wouldn't have a surface in this case it might just be like I described it (an invisible ball of energy). Who knows?

But the reason this video is not answering the question is because what we picture here is the wave function of the atomic orbitals... That's like asking "how does a free kick in football look like" and showing me the equations that govern the trajectory of the ball after the player hit it plotted into a 4D space...

THAS NOT HOW FOOTBALL LOOKS THO! :D

text: Thanks.  That looks like it was a lot of work, and you did a great job with it!  I really feel that we need more philosophy of science in the realm of quantum mechanics.  We need to look QM in the eye and ask, 'What does this really mean?'  I do think it would help if we stopped treating it like the old wave / particle duality idea, and started treated as a true quantum: a standing-wave packet that can (under certain conditions) behave like a single, independent thing.  As a wave, it can spread out or it can contract, depending on circumstances.  Clearly, this is where probability enters the picture.  But it is also a self-contained unit, which is subject to the forces of nature - the fields - and can interact with them, as well as interacting with other wave quanta.  Some phenomenon, such as tunneling, are not so mysterious if seen in this light.  Of course, other ideas, such as non-locality, must still be dealt with.  But let's chose this purely standing-wave quanta idea as a starting point, and go from there.  It'll sure beat the heck out of 'Shut up and calculate!'       tavi.

author: @patrickfreivald7070

text:
@moscanaveia  Yeah it is niche and quite rightfully so if Wolfram's physics project leads anywhere.   

As an interesting aside have you looked at Wolfram's physics project? It's a very different approach as it treats the universe as an evolving Turing machine acting on a informational network array but one of its fascinating prospects is how in the large scale limit emergence of both general relativity and the Feynman path integral formulation of quantum mechanics within the same framework with the latter quantum mechanical part being a space of all possible configurations or "branches" which the system can evolve, similar to but not identical to the "Many Worlds" interpretation of quantum mechanics. Things look weird to us in these dimensions perhaps in part because we are analogous to flatlanders only ever seeing the combined projections of these dimensions (or equivalently an "observation" can be considered a specific reference frame shift a branchial acceleration "kicking" us into a different frame or reference with a different projection)

Point is the Feynman Path integral's convergence towards the lowest action becomes equivalent to gravity's convergence of matter to the lowest energy configuration i.e. stuff attracts stuff and the guiding equation of Bohmian mechanics becomes the branchial component of the metric tensor.

Incidentally you may be able to see where this model deviates from the Many Worlds interpretation as without sufficient energy to resist the branchial pull of gravity the branching (aka quantum measurement) is  going to necessarily fall back down in the absence of something to stabilize the split state against collapse(aka collision?) . Yeah its weird....


This is obviously far from settled as a model in big part because dimension in this model is not a fixed quantity but a dynamic state variable dependent on the properties of the network as space is an emergent bulk property and currently there is no developed formulation of mathematics to account for this type of break down in the concept of well defined dimensions and space at "small" scales. Heck as writing this I realized we don't even have the language to describe such a variation.

For now it is just a curiosity to keep an eye on but with the way things have developed so far that might change within a couple or years or less.
author: @Dragrath1

text: @patrickfreivald7070  We are not "mostly certain" that there are no hidden variables, that's an oversimplification that some people make. It's just that hidden variables would violate locality. But there's nothing that states we need to have locality.
author: @asdfasdfasdf1218

text: @asdfasdfasdf1218  Well, I think a formal criticism of Bohmian Mechanics is probably not best hashed out in a YouTube video's comments, but I'm relatively comfortable with going along with Bell's Theorem at this point.
author: @patrickfreivald7070

text: @patrickfreivald7070  You are wrong. Bell only counters local hidden variables. De Broglie-Bohm does not use any of those.
author: @whuzzzup

text: @patrickfreivald7070  The main reason why Bohmian mechanics is not accepted is that it's fundamentally and irrevocably incompatible with relativity. The world is relativistic, so Bohmian mechanics is experimentally falsified.

text: One thing I like about this approach with randomly-placed dots is that a few of them end up much further out than you usually see in diagrams. For instance, a diagram showing 95% probability will never show outliers, and it can give the wrong impression that there is some sharp boundary to a given orbital. There is no way to make that mistake with these animations. You also see the nodes in the same way, spaces with gradually decreasing numbers of dots, down to a middle where there are none at all.

text: It's because natural language can be clumsy and bulky for describing nature. This is clear in ancient mathematics books, which didn't have the concept of mathematical symbols or equations, and instead stated everything with words, like Euclid's elements. For example, consider this passage: "if a first magnitude and a third are equal multiples of a second and a fourth, and a fifth and a sixth are equal multiples of the second and fourth, then the first magnitude and fifth, being added together, and the third and the sixth, being added together, will also be equal multiples of the second and the fourth, respectively."
author: @asdfasdfasdf1218
@jonathanodude6660

text: @jonathanodude6660  Yes, that's how you write it with symbols as an equation.
author: @asdfasdfasdf1218

text: @jonathanodude6660  Yes, just with more precisely defined words than in everyday English. Words like "if" and "or" are detached from everyday usage, and concepts like "functions" or "mappings," which are the same thing, are given precise definitions, such as "a domain D, a range R, and a collection f of ordered pairs of the form (d, r), d in D, r in R, such that for any d in D, (d, r1) and (d, r2) both in f imply r1=r2" and so on. Everyday language is very loose in meaning and contradictions arise simply from using one meaning and then another causing miscommunication.
author: @asdfasdfasdf1218

text:
@oakpope  I didn't say new ideas couldn't exist, it's just that all ideas have their basis in past experiences. The ideas may be a combination of several experiences, and the experiences could be used in different ways, but ultimately you cannot think of something you've never heard or seen before. You can manipulate the information you already have, but you cannot create new information out of thin air. Take language, for example. You cannot suddenly speak a language you've never heard before. Maybe you can invent a language, but the words of that language will have to come from somewhere. You can speak, because you remember words and sentence structures that have been used in different contexts, and extrapolate on that to create new sentences. The act of speaking functions purely through manipulating memory into new ideas. Ideas are molded from memories.

The human mind needs input to produce output, our brains are worthless without sensations to fill them with something to derive ideas from. Dirac would never have invented his delta function without the background in mathematics and physics needed to even comprehend such an idea. It has its background purely in his experiences and past knowledge.

text: More accurate isn't necessarily better. By the very nature of a model, it is a simplification of what it is portraying. A good model needs to find the balance between being accurate and being simply/easy to use. A globe is more accurate than a map, because it is in 3D, but that very same aspect often makes maps easier to use and therefore they become preferred models, because the inaccuracies doesn't matter or affect us, when we use them for their intended purpose.
author: @Bronzescorpion

text: @Bronzescorpion  Yes I agree, accurate was the wrong word to use. Perhaps  I should have said useful, or at least less misleading. My frustration with the simplistic models growing up was they seemed far too abstract for describing reality, the balance wasn't there.
